<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 26 日星期三 16:07:42 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Dictator Myth That Refuses to Die]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>威权主义者会让你认为他们在某些事情上可以比那些必须处理制衡、制衡和公众舆论的同行做得更好。别相信。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/TpqHzLgeP9It6_WQ0LoQplZ_T38=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/dictators/original.jpg" alt="一张墨索里尼在麦克风前举起拳头的黑白照片似乎已经解体。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/大西洋月刊。资料来源：盖蒂</figcaption></figure>上周，在福克斯新闻的市政厅（还有哪里？），前总统唐纳德·特朗普称中国的独裁者习近平是一个“才华横溢”的人，“用铁拳统治着 14 亿人民”。为了避免有人怀疑他的钦佩，特朗普补充道，习近平“聪明、才华横溢，一切都很完美。好莱坞没有人能像这个人一样。”<br><br>特朗普并不孤单。美国和世界各地的许多人都看到了独裁者的魅力，他不管规则或法律如何阻碍，都能把事情做好，让火车准时运行。根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.voterstudygroup.org/publication/democracy-maybe">反复的民意调查</a>，大约四分之一的美国人同意这样的说法：“一个不必为国会和选举操心的强有力的领导人”是可取的。其他地方有更高比例的公民<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2017/10/16/democracy-widely-supported-little-backing-for-rule-by-strong-leader-or-military/">同意这种观点</a>，包括在一些人口最多的民主国家：55% 的印度人、52% 的印度尼西亚人、38% 的尼日利亚人和 31% 的日本人。<br><br>当政府未能满足民众的期望时，这种对独裁统治的草木皆绿的观点往往最常出现。当民主实现时，独裁似乎并不是一个乐观的选择。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2017/10/16/democracy-widely-supported-little-backing-for-rule-by-strong-leader-or-military/">只有 6%</a>的德国人和 9% 的瑞典人受到强人的诱惑。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/democracy-hold-customer-service-airline-insurance-junk-fees/673201/">布莱恩·克拉斯：民主存在客户服务问题</a><br><br>对独裁统治的崇拜是建立在一个有害的谎言之上的，我称之为“仁慈独裁的神话”。这个神话建立在三个脆弱的支柱之上：首先，独裁者比民主国家带来更强劲的经济增长；其次，独裁者不受不稳定的公众舆论的影响，是战略性的长期思考者；第三，独裁者带来稳定，而分裂的民主国家则产生混乱。<br><br>二十年前，美国及其西方盟友卷入伊拉克战争，随后又陷入金融危机，导致智库开始 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fpc.org.uk/publications/the-beijing-consensus/">称赞“北京共识”</a>或“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/china/archive/2013/03/why-the-china-model-isnt-going-away/274237/">中国模式</a>”作为自由民主的替代方案。在特朗普和英国脱欧时代，对民主的批评激增。在美国，知识分子出版物发表文章认为问题在于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/04/america-tyranny-donald-trump.html">民主太多</a>。 2018年，伦敦<em>《泰晤士报》</em>发表了题为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/our-timid-leaders-can-learn-from-strongmen-3xhqhk0zw">我们胆怯的领导人可以向强人学习</a>”的专栏。中国官方媒体利用西方的民主困境，辩称<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/03/14/china-paper-says-rise-of-racist-trump-shows-democracy-is-scary/">民主是一种“可怕”的制度</a>，会造成自我伤害。<br><br>但过去几年发生的事件和新研究打破了长期以来仁慈独裁的神话。谎言的三大支柱都在崩溃。每一个新的数据点都<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://winstonchurchill.org/resources/quotes/the-worst-form-of-government/">证明温斯顿·丘吉尔是对的</a>：“民主是最糟糕的政府形式，除了不时尝试过的所有其他形式。”<br><br>让我们从独裁统治带来更强劲增长的神话开始。这种谎言源于一些众所周知的、精心挑选的例子，在这些例子中，独裁者监督了国民经济的惊人转变。从 20 世纪 50 年代末开始，李光耀帮助新加坡从一个贫穷、鸦片泛滥的死水区变成了一个富裕的经济强国。而在中国，人均GDP从1990年的近318美元上升到今天的12,500多美元。这些成功令人瞠目结舌。<br><br>但对总体数据的系统评估揭示了另一个现实。即使存在这些强劲增长的异常情况，大多数严格的研究也发现<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dpsa.dk/papers/Nyrup_DPSA.pdf#cite.0@bjornskov2018regime">有限或没有证据</a>表明独裁政权比民主政权产生更好的经济增长。政治经济学家达伦·阿西莫格鲁和詹姆斯·罗宾逊等一些研究人员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/205014/why-nations-fail-by-daron-acemoglu-and-james-a-robinson/">发现了令人信服的证据</a>，表明包容性的民主政治制度是实现稳定、长期增长的最有力因素之一。<br><br>当独裁政权确实在经济上取得成功时，他们往往会付出代价，因为即使是蓬勃发展的独裁政权也容易遭受灾难性的崩溃。正如政治学家雅各布·尼鲁普（Jacob Nyrup）所写：“中国在50年的时间里既经历了饥荒，导致20-4500万人死亡，又经历了经济繁荣，使数亿人摆脱了贫困。”因此，对独裁经济数据最乐观的解释是，独裁者有时可能会实现略高的增长，但经济崩溃的风险要大得多。这不是一个明智的权衡。<br><br>然而，强人作为经济大师的神话还有一个更大的问题。事实证明，独裁者几十年来一直在操纵他们的经济数据。很长一段时间以来，他们一直在愚弄我们。但现在我们有证据：他们的数字有时看起来好得令人难以置信，因为它们确实如此。<br><br>每个政府都有捏造经济数据的动机。但民主国家拥有提供监督并阻止政客冲动的机构，确保数据准确。独裁国家不存在这样的检查。<br><br>这种差异促使芝加哥大学经济学家路易斯·马丁内斯（Luis Martinez）测试独裁者是否<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thedocs.worldbank.org/en/doc/350051528721174623-0050022018/original/Nightlights.pdf">夸大了他们的增长率</a>。他用一种巧妙的方法做到了这一点。先前的研究已经证实，卫星捕获的夜间光量与整体经济活动之间存在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-economics-080217-053355">强大而准确的相关性</a>。当经济增长时，它们会发出更多的夜间光（这就是为什么你可以在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://earth.google.com/web/@37.49351744,-84.10377216,1070.56549039a,7585747.77774096d,35y,0h,0t,0r/data=CisSKRIgMGY3ZTJkYzdlOGExMTFlNjk5MGQ2ZjgxOGQ2OWE2ZTciBWVhcnRo">夜间卫星图像</a>上清楚地辨认出城市，以及为什么非洲的光密度比欧洲或美国东海岸低得多） 。高分辨率图像使研究人员能够跟踪夜间照明随时间的变化，而这些图像产生的详细、精细的数据几乎无法操纵。马丁内斯发现了一个惊人的差异，表明独裁者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://harris.uchicago.edu/news-events/news/qa-luis-martinez-exposes-way-dictators-exaggerate-economic-performance">夸大了他们的 GDP 增长</a>约 35%。<br><br>检查的数字越多，暴露的操纵行为就越多。在卢旺达， <em>《纽约时报》</em>将总统保罗·卡加梅称为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/08/magazine/paul-kagame-rwanda.html">“全球精英最喜爱的强人”</a> ，因为他在经济增长方面有着明显的辉煌记录。该国政府声称，从 2010 年到 2014 年，该国贫困率减少了 6%。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://roape.net/2017/07/26/faking-rwandan-gdp-growth-myth/">研究人员发现</a>，卢旺达的贫困人口减少了 6%。事实恰恰相反：贫困率实际上增加了 5% 到 7%。恰如其分的是，贝尼托·墨索里尼<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-11-15/stop-saying-mussolini-made-the-trains-run-on-time">让火车准点运行的说法是一个谎言</a>。他建造了华丽的车站，并投资了精英阶层使用的火车线路，但通勤大众却被抛在了后面。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/01/xi-jinping-china-economy-jack-ma/617552/">阅读：中国经济奇迹的毁灭</a><br><br>即使是中国这个明显的专制经济奇迹，也显示出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2023/07/18/china-economy-gdp-decline-deflation-real-estate-zero-covid/">放缓的迹象</a>，其增长模式<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/china-economy-outlook-growth-model-globalization-exports-middle-income-trap-2023-7?r=US&amp;IR=T">不再与全球经济相匹配</a>。这种增长的裂缝是独裁制度的固有特征。由于独裁政权将异见定为犯罪，正常的经济反馈机制被打破，系统在犯下经济错误时无法自我纠正。北京方面不切实际地寻求维持永久的“零新冠病毒”就是一个很好的例子。独裁者擅长建设港口、道路和矿山。但繁荣的现代经济不是靠露天矿井而是靠开放的思想来维持的，独裁政权从设计上就限制了开放思想的供应。<br><br>仁慈独裁神话的拥护者很容易忽视一个关键事实，即独裁国家的增长很大程度上要么来自于更开放的民主西方社会发明的制造业产品，要么来自向富裕民主国家出口商品。 （中国出口的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://oec.world/en/profile/country/chn">主要目的地</a>是美国、日本和韩国。）这样一来，即使是独裁增长的异类，其成功也依赖于民主国家的创新和消费者财富。如果民主的美国没有首先成为经济强国，中国会如此迅速地通过出口导向型增长让数百万人摆脱贫困吗？<br><br>事实证明，神话的第二根支柱并不比第一根更脆弱。它认为独裁者比民主者更具战略性的长期思想家，因为他们不受变化无常的公众舆论的影响。但只有当你不了解大多数独裁政权的实际运作方式时，这个谎言才可信。<br><br>十多年来，我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/corruptible-who-gets-power-and-how-it-changes-us-brian-klaas/16255009?ean=9781982154103">研究并采访了暴君</a>及其周围的追随者。我得出的一个结论是，根据错误信息做出决策是独裁者运行的系统的固有特征。独裁者掌握权力的时间越长，他们就越有可能陷入我所说的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/03/putin-dictator-trap-russia-ukraine/627064/">独裁者陷阱</a>”，他们镇压异议，清洗任何挑战他们的人，并通过宣传构建自己的现实，所有这些都是为了维持控制。在这样的系统中，向权力说出真相实际上可能是致命的。结果，独裁者只被告知他们想听的，而不是真实的，他们开始相信自己的谎言。弗拉基米尔·普京在乌克兰发生的灾难性战争是独裁者陷阱的悲惨例证：普京因自己的供应而得意忘形，而无辜的乌克兰人却成为他权力之旅的受害者。<br><br>暴君常常利用自己的权力，不是为了长期规划，而是为了短期的自我荣耀，这一点不胜枚举。土库曼斯坦前独裁者萨帕尔穆拉特·尼亚佐夫（Saparmurat Niyazov）斥资数百万美元 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11095257">，为了纪念他自己，建造了一座永远面向太阳旋转的金色雕像</a>。他的另一项天才之举是， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4307583.stm">关闭了所有乡村医院</a>，以便病人能够有幸在他的原始大理石首都阿什哈巴德接受治疗。大多数人居住在城外，无数人可能因为无法及时到达医院而死亡。他的继任者为他最喜欢的狗品种竖立了一座<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-54894828">巨大的金色雕像</a>。值得庆幸的是，民主国家有制衡机制来抑制这种自恋的冲动。<br><br>然而，这一神话最持久的支柱是认为独裁者能带来稳定。一些独裁者已经掌权数十年。穆阿迈尔·卡扎菲去世前统治利比亚 42 年。喀麦隆的保罗·比亚 (Paul Biya) 是一位 89 岁的独裁者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/africa/2023-01-23-africas-oldest-president-forgets-where-he-is-while-addressing-global-summit/">，他在最近的一次活动中不知道自己身在何处</a>，他在越南战争期间上任。普京执政已有二十多年；迄今为止，习近平只做出了一项裁决，但他似乎准备无限期地保留自己的职位。<br><br>为了保持权力，独裁领导人面临不断的权衡。如果他们加强军事或准军事领导人的力量，他们就会面临政变的风险。但如果他们削弱了自己的武装力量，那么他们就无法保护自己免受外部入侵。为了让精英阶层满意，独裁者需要通过腐败让他们变得富有——通常是以牺牲民众为代价。但一个充斥着不义之财的统治阶级可能会引发一场革命，或者一个变数：暗杀。独裁者看似稳定，但其实不然。他们总是很脆弱，被迫做出每一个决定，以避开威胁，以求在权力中生存。<br><br>具有讽刺意味的是，专制国家确实存在的稳定部分源于民主的陷阱。最近的研究表明，独裁者已经开发出“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ciaotest.cc.columbia.edu/journals/twq/v37i4/f_0033652_27429.pdf">模仿民主以延长独裁统治</a>”的机制。大多数独裁领导人现在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300246650/how-to-rig-an-election/">都会举行选举，但会操纵选举</a>。有些人利用议会或法院<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/rule-by-law/64D05AB3BEAFEE4C86E01883B9A143DC">制定不受欢迎的决定</a>，同时避免受到指责。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/12/the-autocrats-are-winning/620526/">摘自 2021 年 12 月号：坏人正在获胜</a><br><br>但最终独裁政权往往会崩溃。当他们崩溃时，他们<em>真的</em>崩溃了。民主国家的选举改变的是政府，而不是政权。相比之下，个人独裁政权常常会崩溃。卡扎菲被杀后，利比亚解体。他有意设计了一个只有以他为中心才能发挥作用的政治体系。普京治下的俄罗斯也可能如此。当他被推翻或去世时，国家将不会有一个平稳、和平的过渡。<br><br>独裁者往往灾难性的灭亡会造成负反馈循环。近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanderbilt.edu/csdi/events/Geddes927.pdf">十分之七的个人独裁领导人</a>一旦失去权力就会被监禁、流放或杀害。许多独裁者在掌权期间都意识到了这一严峻的事实，因此他们使用暴力来维持权力，并且在走向垮台时往往变得更加极端。即使同一个人在宫殿里呆了几十年，这种效果也很难被称为“稳定”。<br><br>对于那些仍然抱有独裁政权可能繁荣、战略明智或内部稳定的幻想的人，我建议进行一个简单的测试。想象一下，有人把世界上所有国家的名字写在小纸条上，然后把它们分成两顶帽子：一顶代表民主，一顶代表独裁。你会选择两顶帽子中的一顶，从中抽出一张纸条，看看名字，然后在那个国家度过余生。谁知道呢，也许你会很幸运，最终进入一个看起来稳定并正在稳定增长的独裁政权。但我知道我会选择哪顶帽子。即使你幻想找到一只仁慈的强人独角兽，我怀疑你也会这样做。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/authorarianism-dictatorship-effectness-china/674820/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/authorarianism-dictatorship-effectness-china/674820/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The 2024 Election Could Be the End of the Cases Against Donald Trump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>全国最有权势的办公室为他提供了终止针对他的案件的最佳机会。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/c1zeQnPhyPUyfW_SccJ8rdMC4tQ=/0x0:3514x1977/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1439325943-1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普戴着“让美国再次伟大”帽子的照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>麦克纳米/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>如果唐纳德·特朗普（看起来很可能）成为明年的共和党总统候选人，那么 2024 年的选举将是对几个关键问题的公投：美国威权主义的前景、充满活力的民主的延续、行政部门与政府之间的关系。其他两个政府部门，以及其他许多具有重大意义的部门。<br><br>这也将是一次关于特朗普是否会对其行为承担法律责任的公投。特朗普面临多起民事诉讼和至少两起刑事起诉（还有两起似乎即将到来）。如果特朗普赢得连任，几乎可以肯定这些问题都不会得到解决——至少不会以不利于他利益的方式得到解决，任何合理的制度都会承认这种可能性。这就是总统的权力。<br><br>首先来看最简单的案件：他因违反与保留机密文件有关的《间谍法》而在佛罗里达州等待起诉，以及他预计因与 1 月 6 日叛乱有关的行动而受到起诉。如果特朗普当选，这些案件都不会导致对特朗普有罪的最终判决（更不用说监禁）。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-second-term-isolationist-fascism/674791/">克里斯托弗·布朗宁：一种新型法西斯主义</a><br><br>海湖庄园文件案定于 2024 年 5 月开庭审理。尽管许多人怀疑这一审理日期会推迟（并非没有根据），但让我们姑且考虑一下审判如期进行且在 6 月某个时间进行的可能性或者 2024 年 7 月，陪审团判定特朗普有罪。毫无疑问，特朗普会对这样的判决提出上诉，同样几乎毫无疑问，主审法官艾琳·坎农(Aileen Cannon)将允许他在上诉中保持自由。<br><br>在我的职业生涯中，我处理过多起刑事上诉。即使是最简单的情况，在不到一年的时间内也没有得到解决。这就是我们上诉系统的运作方式；诉讼程序根本没有紧迫感（需要明确的是，在正常的业务过程中也不应该有紧迫感——审判已经结束，记录完整；对这些诉讼程序进行成熟和深思熟虑的审查需要时间）。结果是，特朗普对其联邦定罪的上诉（假设一项得到保证）很可能仍在第十一巡回法院悬而未决，该法院对佛罗里达州的联邦审判拥有上诉管辖权，至少到 2025 年中期——远远超过了选举和进入下一个总统任期。即使上诉能够很快结束，特朗普也不可避免地会向最高法院申请复审，这需要更多的时间。<br><br>类似的日历将适用于可能很快由华盛顿特区的特别检察官提出的 1 月 6 日相关指控，即使该审判比佛罗里达州的审判更快进行（例如，在 3 月或 4 月）明年（这是一个很大的假设，因为联邦法院必须就一项有效的审判进行谈判，并且与原定于 3 月在纽约举行的审判不冲突），向对案件拥有管辖权的华盛顿特区巡回法院提出上诉的机会从首都联邦法院到最高法院，不到 10 个月的时间几乎为零。<br><br>简而言之，在我看来，针对特朗普的任何联邦指控都不可能在 2025 年 1 月 20 日之前最终确定——根本不可能。同样可以肯定的是，特朗普任命的总检察长（无论是谁）的首要行动之一就是司法部采取行动，驳回针对总统的案件，无论案件处于悬而未决的阶段。简而言之，如果特朗普在 2024 年 11 月赢得连任，针对他的联邦案件很可能会在他就职后 24 小时内终止，而没有最终解决方案。这并不意味着这些程序毫无价值。如果特朗普在任何一次审判中被定罪，美国将受益于确定其犯罪行为的历史记录。但当我们再忍受他四年的统治，并且他继续避免任何表面上的实际责任时，这并不能让人感到安慰。<br><br>当我们转向特朗普在纽约已悬而未决的案件以及预计不久将在佐治亚州审理的另一起案件中面临的州指控时，情况变得更加复杂。根据定义（至少就宪法而言），这些州是独立的主权国家，特朗普领导下的联邦政府不能指示驳回那些针对他的案件，特朗普也不能赦免自己在州的罪行，因为他的赦免权是同样，仅限于联邦事务。因此，这些案件将会继续进行。<br><br>但天哪，他们很难得到解决。<br><br>首先，我们可以相信特朗普领导的司法部认为，现任总统至少在任职期间不受州起诉。他们的主张也有一定的道理。毕竟，如果纽约和佐治亚州地方检察官可以在特朗普任职期间对他进行审判，那么任何反对总统的州的民选官员都可能利用其权力对总统提出当地刑事指控。如何阻止一位民选共和党检察官在一个非常红色的州对乔·拜登总统提出虚假指控？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-hunter-biden-indictment-plea-deal/674543/">凯特·肖：反应揭示了特朗普与拜登的一切</a><br><br>风险超出了假设。我们已经看到当选的总检察长如何以更加政治化的方式使用他们的权力。从“合理”起诉到“不公正”起诉的飞跃主要取决于旁观者的看法。这就是为什么50多年前，水门事件特别检察官办公室在这一点上实际上站在总统一边，声称“出于联邦制的考虑，将禁止在州法院起诉他”。宪法文本中没有任何内容禁止国家起诉行政长官，但也没有授权这样做，因此这个问题从未得到明确解决。但如果特朗普当选，我们可以肯定，最高法院会做出什么决定，谁也说不准。<br><br>这也不是州检察官需要克服的唯一法律障碍。特朗普要求将纽约起诉移交给联邦法院的努力迄今已被拒绝， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/politics/judge-us-cant-replace-trump-e-jean-carroll-slander-suit">联邦政府在一些针对他的民事诉讼中取代特朗普的努力也被</a>拒绝。然而，如果特朗普重返办公室，这些论点将具有更大的影响力。他作为联邦官员的身份以及他个人对民事诉讼的责任所造成的对政府活动的干扰将变得更加明显。特朗普任命的总检察长几乎肯定会在法庭上尽最大努力向他们施压。<br><br>其他挑战可能不那么合法，但本质上更实际。如果纽约和佐治亚州坚持他们的立场，特朗普报复的性质将仅受他的想象力的限制。例如，如果他试图从这两个州撤回联邦执法资金，会发生什么？如果他指示联邦调查局退出合作调查工作怎么办？如果在共和党领导的佐治亚州，他向州立法机构施压，要求其通过法律限制亚特兰大地方检察官的权力或要求她驳回此案，结果会怎样？国家不应该回答这些问题。<br><br>如果特朗普再次当选，几乎肯定会避免对其犯罪行为承担责任，这一前景只是他对法治构成的更广泛威胁的一小部分。但这是一种具有象征意义的可能性，散发着王权的气息。可悲的是，现实是显而易见的：当美国人在 2024 年参加投票时，如果特朗普是候选人，他们将不会简单地在两种政治选择之间进行选择；他们会做出选择。他们也将做出该国历史上最重要的选择之一。他们将在“没有人凌驾于法律之上”的现代信念和回到政治领导人可以不受惩罚的时代之间做出选择。我们自己的民族性格取决于我们做出的选择。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 12:18:49 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-candidacy-criminal-appeal/674827/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-candidacy-criminal-appeal/674827/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Wrath of Goodreads]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>作者受到那些懒得阅读他们作品的人的摆布。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/DcJB2yRT39HblID42TYJ8YY2-uc=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/goodreads_final_3/original.jpg" alt="穿过书本的箭头" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>当梅根·诺兰出版她的第一部小说时，其他作家用“不祥的语气”警告她有关 Goodreads 网站的问题。这位年轻的爱尔兰作家在 2020 年冬天查看了这本书的列表，那天第一本校样到达了她家。 “除了我和出版商之外，没有人见过它，”她最近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/books/2023/07/goodreads-book-reviews-degrading-literary-culture">写道</a>。 “尽管如此，它已经收到了一条评论：两颗星，是由一个与我有无关紧要的个人不和的人留下的。他根本不可能读过这本书。”<br><br> Goodreads的可怕威力在出版界是公开的秘密。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2013/04/the-simple-reason-why-goodreads-is-so-valuable-to-amazon/274548/">亚马逊于 2013 年收购的</a>这个评论网站可以塑造围绕一本书或作者的对话，无论是积极的还是消极的。如今，表面上的口碑热门作品通常是通过 Goodreads 或 Instagam 和 TikTok 等社交网络在网上创建的。<br><br>出版商知道这些动态的重要性，因此他们不仅向可能库存图书的独立书商，而且还向可能制作相关内容的影响者发送高级阅读副本（ARC）。 “有一种假设是，如果你收到 ARC，你就会发布有关它的信息，”文学播客<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thestackspodcast.com/about/"><em>The Stacks</em></a>的主持人 Traci Thomas 告诉我，“无论是在你的 Goodreads 上，在你的 Instagram 上，在你的 TikTok 上，告诉其他人在你的书店，或者其他什么地方。所以这就是为什么一本尚未出版的书有这么多评论的结果。”<br><br>许多图书博主都认真地在自己的帖子中添加免责声明，感谢出版商为他们提供 ARC“以换取诚实的评论”。但公开免费赠品远不是合同要求，甚至不是社会规范。因此，你无法轻易辨别哪些早期评论家真正读过这本书，哪些评论家可能会对社交媒体的讨论做出反应（或者，正如诺兰在她的案例中所怀疑的那样，是在诉诸个人恩怨）。<br><br>这很重要，因为病毒式营销活动始终针对未出版的书籍。通常会发生的情况是，Instagram 或 TikTok 上的一个有影响力的声音认为一本书“有问题”，然后该人的数十名粉丝前往 Goodreads，让作者的冒犯更加广为人知。回应这些攻击的作者可能会让情况变得更糟。凯瑟琳·黑尔（Kathleen Hale）对一位刻薄的评论者感到非常愤怒，以至于她找到了这位女士的地址，她后来<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/oct/18/am-i-being-catfished-an-author-confronts-her-number-one-online-critic">写道</a>，该网站警告她不要订婚：“在页面底部，Goodreads 发布了以下指令（如果您已登录）作为一名作者，它出现在你写的每本书的差评之后）：“我们真的，真的（真的！）认为你不应该对此评论发表评论，甚至不应该感谢审稿人。”大多数作者我知道阅读他们的 Goodreads 评论，然后独自默默地对他们感到愤怒。因为我是个怪人，所以我从自己身上获得了巨大的乐趣——抱怨越琐碎、莫名其妙越好。 “我听了有声读物，到了第三章，她在‘男性’这个词之前的停顿开始让我恼火，”我的书《<em>难相处的女人》</em>的一篇评论中写道。<br><br>当投诉越来越多、越来越严重时，就被称为“评论轰炸”或“结队”。 Goodreads 闪电战可能会破坏整个出版计划，吓坏计划讨论发行的商业读书俱乐部，甚至促使紧张的出版商削减有争议书籍的营销预算。上个月，《<em>美食、祈祷、爱情》</em>的作者伊丽莎白·吉尔伯特 (Elizabeth Gilbert) 撤回了她即将出版的小说<em>《雪林》(The Snow Forest)</em> ，原因是她透露小说以苏联为背景后遭到强烈反对。 <em>《雪森林》</em>的 Goodreads 页面指责她将俄罗斯灵魂浪漫化，该页面现已被删除。 “我会为你裁掉这份工作——他们没有，”一位评论者写道。另一位写道：“就像她在<em>这部</em>小说中的角色不知道二战事件一样，伊丽莎白·吉尔伯特本人似乎也不知道俄罗斯现在正在对乌克兰进行种族灭绝战争，因为我确信她是否知道，她会意识到这本书是多么的聋子。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/06/elizabeth-gilbert-book-release-postponed-ukraine-war/674379/">阅读：吃饭、祈祷、迎合</a><br><br>这本书原定于明年二月出版，但在一段视频中宣布“现在不是出版这本书的时候”，吉尔伯特基本上赞同 Goodreads 的批评：“我不想给一群那些已经经历过并且正在继续遭受严重和极端伤害的人。”<br><br>现在，我不知道<em>《雪林》</em>是否让俄罗斯人的灵魂变得浪漫，或者是否会对乌克兰人造成“伤害”。和我的同事富兰克林·福尔一样，我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/06/elizabeth-gilbert-book-release-postponed-ukraine-war/674379/">发现这些指控令人难以置信</a>。但显而易见的事实是，我们都不知道，因为——这应该是显而易见的，尽管最近的事件表明事实并非如此<em>——你不知道一本你没有读过的书里有什么</em>。你也不知道你没有看过的电影、你没有听过的专辑、或者你没有点击过的文章中有什么。这曾经很重要。现在不再这样了，因为我们生活在一个你可以通过传播头条新闻的屏幕截图和断章取义的视频剪辑来获得点赞的世界，而且营销活动规模足够大，它们本身就构成了艺术陈述。 （<em>芭比</em>，我在看着你。）<br><br>不幸的是，在这种病毒般的地狱景观中最有可能遇到麻烦的艺术作品是那些探索复杂的、煽动性主题的艺术作品，例如性、种族和身份。 Goodreads 的另一部电视剧<em>《一切都很好》</em>最近播出，这是塞西莉亚·拉贝斯 (Cecilia Rabess) 撰写的处女作，于 6 月 6 日出版。该剧的情节围绕一位年轻、进步的黑人女性，在唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 上台前爱上了一位保守的白人。选举。拉贝斯告诉我，“它显然解决了美国有关种族、阶级、政治和身份的一些避雷针问题”，因此她预计 Goodreads 和类似网站会引起强烈反响。 “但我认为人们肯定没有读过这本书。所以我不知道他们是如何得出这样的结论的——这本书没有仔细、深思熟虑或有意地处理这些主题。”<br><br>将这种描述视为作家的轻描淡写。 “如果你用它来为种族主义者开脱，那它就不是恋人的敌人，”一篇典型的一星评论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:NBNOok5wJxMJ:https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/62919844&amp;cd=6&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;gl=uk">写道</a>，引用了一个常见的浪漫小说比喻。 “有些作者不应该成为作者，这是什么鬼！？”另一个提供了。 “我还没有读过这本书，也不打算读，但读过概要后，我将其评为一星，”第三位承认。<br><br>就<em>《一切都很好》</em>而言，这种批评似乎是从 TikTok 开始的，一些著名的创作者批评了这本书。随后，愤怒的情绪蔓延到 Goodreads，那些创作者的粉丝可以在那里表达他们的不满。 “我没有也不会读这篇文章，我来自抖音，我希望销量如此糟糕，以至于书店不得不扔掉所有库存，因为它拒绝出售。任何获得 ARC 的人都应该感到羞耻，”另一条一星评论指出。<br><br>对于拉贝斯来说，这段经历是残酷的。 “作为一名艺术家，你要做好人们不会与你的作品产生共鸣的心理准备，”她说。 “但我认为，当人们认为你自己有问题，或者你自己造成伤害，或者他们用任何语言来描述它时，感觉会有所不同。感觉有点超现实。”这种强烈的反对可能在 Goodreads 上很盛行，但很快就蔓延到了更广泛的互联网上。拉贝斯是黑人，她收到了愤怒的直接信息和电子邮件，以及她发布的任何社交媒体帖子下的辱骂性评论。 “他们说我和我的孩子们的坏话。叫我<em>浣熊</em>，还有其他令人不快的辱骂。告诉我，我还不如死了好。”<br><br>愤怒是四散的。使用种族诽谤的评论者显然知道拉贝斯的种族，但她想知道其他一些在线评论家是否认为她是一名白人作家，侵犯了他们认为应该为有色人种作家保留的领域。虽然作者被明智地告知不要阅读评论——当然也不要与批评者打交道——但当批评者直接出现在你的（虚拟）面前并向你大喊他们的观点时，这就更难了。<br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/164999338-the-snow-forest">阅读：正在扼杀创造力的公司</a><br><br>碰巧的是，播客特雷西·托马斯 (Traci Thomas) 也是不喜欢拉贝斯这本书的人之一——尽管是在一月份读过预印本之后。 “这是一本令人讨厌的书，”她告诉我。她反对她所认为的故事的寓意：爱征服一切，即使是特朗普的支持者。 “书中的男朋友乔什戴着一顶让美国再次伟大的帽子，就像对[女主角]说种族主义的废话。她说，<em>没关系</em>。对她来说最大的启示是她仍然可以选择爱他。我就想：好吧，酷，走吧——我要把这本书撕成碎片。”<br><br>最终，托马斯总结道：“我不知道这本书是否需要存在。”<br><br> Despite her own strong feelings, Thomas told me that she sometimes felt uneasy about her own reviews being surrounded by knee-jerk reactions and “performative allyship,” even by people whose politics she shared. “There are people who are new to anti-racism work or supporting LGBTQ people, or disability activism or whatever. And they feel it is their job to call out things that they notice without perhaps understanding the bigger historical context.” To illustrate the point, she gave an example: Imagine an author writes a book about Black children riding tricycles, “and then I&#39;ll see a review that&#39;s like, &#39;This book didn&#39;t talk about Black preschoolers who ride bikes, and they&#39;re also at risk.&#39;”<br><br> That dynamic explains one of the most initially counterintuitive aspects of viral pile-ons: that many seem to target authors who would agree with their critics on 99 percent of their politics. A strange kind of progressive one-upmanship is at work here: Anyone can condemn Ann Coulter&#39;s latest book, but pointing out the flaws in a feminist or anti-racist book, or a novel by a Black female author, establishes the critic as the occupant of a higher moral plane.<br><br> The net effect of this is to hobble books by progressive authors such as Gilbert, and by writers of color such as Rabess. The latter is philosophical about the controversy over <em>Everything&#39;s Fine</em> , seeing the backlash as representative of the political moment she was exploring in the novel—of “people feeling a dearth of community and connection, and just wanting a way to connect, a way to express themselves or express their anger.”<br><br> Of course, if Goodreads wanted to, it could fix the review-bombing problem overnight. When services that rely on user-generated content are only lightly moderated, it&#39;s always a conscious decision, and usually a cold commercial one. After Gilbert pulled her novel from publication, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/07/01/amazon-goodreads-elizabeth-gilbert/"><em>The Washington Post</em></a> observed that Amazon, which reportedly paid $150 million for Goodreads, now shows little interest in maintaining or updating the site. Big changes to a heavily trafficked site can be costly and risk annoying the existing user base: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-06-21/reddit-blackout-previews-social-media-s-future-in-the-ai-era">Reddit</a> has recently faced down a moderators&#39; revolt for changes to how developers can access its tools, and Elon Musk&#39;s tenure at Twitter—or whatever it&#39;s now called—will one day be taught at business schools on a slide headlined “How to Lose Advertisers and Alienate People.” A purge of duplicate accounts might sweep up some fanatically devoted Goodreads users—people who can&#39;t bear to share their opinion only once—and make the site feel less busy and exciting.<br><br> Goodreads spokesperson Suzanne Skyvara told me by email that the site “takes the responsibility of maintaining the authenticity and integrity of ratings and protecting our community of readers and authors very seriously.” She added that Goodreads is working to “stay ahead of content and accounts that violate our <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/guidelines">reviews</a> or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.goodreads.com/community/guidelines">community</a> guidelines” and has “increased the number of ways members can flag content to us.”<br><br> The main Amazon site has several measures in place to stop review-bombing: Reviews from verified purchasers of books are flagged as such to bolster their credibility, while the star rating is the product of a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/story/amazon-stars-ratings-calculated/">complicated algorithm</a> rather than simply an average of all the review scores. Goodreads could adopt even more stringent measures—but then, it isn&#39;t in the company&#39;s interests to reduce volume in favor of quality, because its entire appeal is based around being a grassroots voice. “Goodreads really needs a mechanism for stopping one-star attacks on writers,” the writer Roxane Gay<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/rgay/status/1668336078447869952?s=20">tweeted</a> after Gilbert&#39;s statement in June. “It undermines what little credibility they have left.” Traci Thomas agrees. In an email, she told me that she would like to see “verified users or reviews that get a check (or something) in exchange for proving they&#39;ve read the book.”<br><br> If Amazon will not put the resources into controlling the wrath of Goodreads, then what fairness requires here is a strong taboo: <em>Do not review a book you haven&#39;t read</em> . We should stigmatize uninformed opinions the way we stigmatize clipping your nails on public transport, talking with your mouth full, or claiming that your <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-42880690">peacock</a> is a service animal. A little self-control from the rest of us will make it easier for writers to approach incendiary topics, safe in the knowledge that they will be criticized only for things they&#39;ve actually done.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 12:15:22 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/goodreads-review-bombing-amazon-moderation/674811/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/goodreads-review-bombing-amazon-moderation/674811/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[What Kind of Villain Doesn’t Clean Up After Their Dog?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> You can lead a dog to grass, but you can&#39;t make his human scoop. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/WrG4WzNxadNyrdFX3WqlEU4AiMs=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/dog_poop/original.jpg" alt="A man hurriedly walks away from another man, who is standing near a fire hydrant with two small white dogs." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Carolyn Drake / Magnum</figcaption></figure> A certain substance is enjoying a renaissance in New York City. In a time of scarcity, it is newly abundant. In a period of economic inflation, it is free and distributed so generously that it might even be on your shoe right now. The substance is dog waste—and <em>lots</em> of people are mad about it.<br><br> In response to an uptick in complaints, the city&#39;s Department of Sanitation <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://people.com/pets/new-york-city-crack-down-on-dog-owners-not-picking-up-dog-poop/">announced in 2022</a> that it would crack down on human delinquents who leave behind their canine companions&#39; droppings. In a statement at the time, the sanitation commissioner, Jessica Tisch, said there would be greater efforts to enforce the $250 fine currently on the books. As part of the fanfare, City Councilmember Erik Bottcher unveiled an awareness campaign informing New Yorkers that “there is no poop fairy.” However, in 2022 the city issued only <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://gothamist.com/news/nycs-sidewalks-covered-in-dog-poop-rule-for-pickup-hardly-enforced">18 tickets</a> for failure to pick up dog waste. In 2023, complaints to the 311 hotline about it have risen by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/01/hamilton-heights-is-neighborhood-with-most-dog-poop-in-nyc/">17 percent</a> .<br><br><p lang="en"> The best part of our dog poop press conference was the groan of disappointment when I announced there is no Poop Fairy. In all seriousness, I want to thank <a href="https://twitter.com/NYCSanitation?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">@nycsanitation</a> for agreeing to my request for more Pooper Scooper Law enforcement officers in Council District 3. <a href="https://t.co/X5Lq38biid">pic.twitter.com/X5Lq38biid</a></p> — Erik Bottcher (@ebottcher) <a href="https://twitter.com/ebottcher/status/1518223009202552835?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">April 24, 2022</a> New York City Councilmember Julie Menin has also been on the receiving end of a grievance deluge. She told me that her office has been “flooded with complaints” (just a “tremendous amount of complaints,” she said) about what her constituents perceive as an increase in sidewalk waste. Most of the complaints were about the areas around schools: kids stepping in it, strollers wheeling in it.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/11/dog-poo-environmental-tragedy/546611/">Read: Dog poo, an environmental tragedy</a><br><br> Menin shared with me a recent study in which researchers found an average of 31,000 fecal bacteria per 100 milliliters of puddle water from New York City&#39;s sidewalks. “In comparison, a public beach would be shut down” at such levels, she said.<br><br> Though I&#39;ve never been under the impression that New York City puddles are a clean place to swim, I agree that having so much fecal bacteria splashing around is suboptimal. In fact, although I haven&#39;t done the polling, I&#39;m comfortable assuming that <em>most</em> people would prefer to keep unplanned encounters with feces at a minimum. And yet it remains an issue across the country. New York isn&#39;t even the city with the worst dog-waste problem; according to a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dogadvisorycouncil.com/foul-play-americas-best-and-worst-behaved-dog-owners-revealed/">2023</a> survey that measured complaints made on Twitter, that honor goes to Seattle.<br><br> This issue obviously has more to do with humans than with dogs, who cannot pick up after themselves and are, in fact, perfect. But humans know better. So why is humanity seemingly unable to solve this problem?<br><br> That people should bear the responsibility of cleaning up after their canine friends seems a given now. The obviousness of it reminds me of an argument I once had with a college roommate who claimed the dishes his visiting girlfriend left behind in the sink were not his responsibility. Well—whose responsibility were they, then? (I&#39;m still angry.) But the expectation that people will pick up after their dogs is relatively new, and was at first seen by many as completely ridiculous.<br><br> In 1978, New York State passed a law that said, “It shall be the duty of each dog owner … to remove any feces left by his or her dog on any sidewalk, gutter, street, or other public area.” Although the so-called poop-scoop law wasn&#39;t technically the first of its kind (Nutley, a small New Jersey suburb, passed one in 1971), it is the legislation most often credited with the American public&#39;s shift in attitude toward dog waste. Alan Beck, New York City&#39;s director of the Bureau of Animal Affairs at the time, succinctly explained its impact in a paper published in the journal <em>Environment</em> in 1979. “When something happens in New York—and it works—it becomes world news,” he wrote.<br><br> I spoke with Beck, now a professor of animal ecology at Purdue University, in Indiana, about the struggle to get the law passed. One of the most vocal proponents of the law at the time, he said, was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/20/nyregion/20lee.html">Fran Lee</a> , the leader of the activist group Children Before Dogs. Lee was particularly concerned about <em>Toxocara canis</em> , a species of roundworm sometimes found in dog feces that can become especially harmful when ingested by children. (The specter of children eating dog feces is somewhat of a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jezebel.com/city-combats-dog-poop-problem-with-image-of-little-girl-514552269">running theme</a> in the dog-feces activist community.) Lee believed that dogs should be required to relieve themselves exclusively within <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1972/08/20/archives/to-scoop-or-not-to-scoop-activist-fran-lee-maintains-that-dirty.html">the confines of their human&#39;s apartment</a> . Though her views were extreme—Beck recalled attending a talk she gave in New Jersey, at which she was pelted with bags of dog waste by an opponent—John Lindsay, New York City&#39;s mayor from 1966 until 1973, sided with her, at least insofar as he believed dog waste was a problem in need of a legislative solution.<br><br> Lindsay proposed a pick-up law in 1972 and was met with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1972/08/20/archives/to-scoop-or-not-to-scoop-activist-fran-lee-maintains-that-dirty.html">outrage</a> . Some animal-rights groups opposed it, fearful that forcing this task would lead people to abandon their dogs, or worse: that acquiescing to this law might embolden the city to ban dogs altogether, a future some saw as Fran Lee&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1972/08/20/archives/to-scoop-or-not-to-scoop-activist-fran-lee-maintains-that-dirty.html">ultimate goal</a> .<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2020/12/it-okay-let-my-dog-sleep-my-bed/617328/">Read: Is it okay to let my dog sleep in my bed?</a><br><br> The proposal didn&#39;t pass, and Lindsay&#39;s term ended. The scooper movement didn&#39;t get its win until Ed Koch was elected in 1977. Right before he took office, State Senator <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/12/nyregion/franz-s-leichter-dead.html">Franz S. Leichter</a> and Assemblyman Edward H. Lehner got the law passed at the state level. The law, which applied to cities in New York with populations greater than 400,000 (meaning only New York City and Buffalo), stated that those who failed to pick up would receive what was at that point a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1984/06/16/nyregion/6-years-of-canine-waste-law-all-in-all-a-cleaner-new-york.html">$25</a> fine. Part of Beck&#39;s job was to explain to residents that the law was “not anti-dog”; he argued that waste-free streets would be healthier for dogs, and would make dog ownership be seen as more acceptable (that is, to landlords and Fran Lee types).<br><br> Though it isn&#39;t possible to quantify the exact amount of dog waste on sidewalks at any particular moment, Beck told me the law seemed to turn things around rather quickly. “Within the first few months,” he said, “people started, whether it&#39;s real or perceived, to feel that things were better.” Now the once-radical proposition is the norm in much of the country.<br><br> With decades of scooping behind us now, it&#39;s frustrating that the task is still an issue that necessitates citywide PR campaigns. Most people who don&#39;t pick up <em>must</em> understand that what they&#39;re doing is wrong. They know they&#39;re leaving behind an unsanitary nuisance for their neighbors and, if they do it in their own neighborhood, themselves. So why do they do it?<br><br> The German sociologist Matthias Gross was curious about the motivations behind these delinquents, so he dedicated 10 years to essentially <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://harpers.org/archive/2015/08/doctoral-feces/">stalking them</a> . Posting up in parks in different cities at various times of the day, he observed the behavior of humans who did and did not scoop, looking for patterns; these eventually ended up as a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/23251042.2014.965402">report</a> —“Natural Waste: Canine Companions and the Lure of Inattentively Pooping in Public”—in the journal <em>Environmental Sociology</em> .<br><br> “I just found that whole phenomenon, from a sociological perspective, so fascinating,” Gross told me. He found that people were less likely to pick up early in the morning, but some of those same non-scoopers <em>would</em> scoop in the afternoon. In his report, Gross suggests that people might not actually care about keeping the parks clean as much as they do about being perceived as good citizens. It brings to mind the concept of the tragedy of the commons—the idea that people tend to act selfishly when given access to something communal, in this case shared social spaces. But if everyone acted selfishly, that communal resource would be ruined.<br><br> To cover up the fact that they were neglecting their responsibility, Gross wrote, many non-scoopers pretended they weren&#39;t aware of what their dog was getting up to. (I have personally seen this particular move many times.) “I saw how dog owners use the iPhone to pretend they were not seeing what the dog is doing,” he told me, adding that the devices “help very much to strategically pretend that you do not know what&#39;s going on.” Indeed—in this situation and others.<br><br> But, of course, we can&#39;t actually know what these people were thinking. Gross&#39;s report was limited primarily to observation, in no small part because when he approached dog owners to discuss why they chose not to pick up what their dog had just expelled, many of them yelled at him. Someone would need to find a way to get inside their minds.<br><br> When she was a grad student, Clodagh Lyons-Bastian, now a lecturer in the department of communication at North Carolina State University, sought to be that brave soul. When a citizens advisory council she was involved with in Raleigh, North Carolina, started getting angry complaints about dogs fouling up a park where local kids played sports, she decided to look more closely at why it was happening.<br><br> In a self-reported <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://chass.ncsu.edu/news/2016/05/12/the-scoop-on-dog-poop/">survey</a> of 1,000 local dog owners, more than 60 percent claimed that when they left waste behind, it was because they didn&#39;t have a bag. Other main categories were because of external circumstances such as rain, or because they were in a wooded area and thought they could just push it to the side and move on. “There wasn&#39;t really anybody who said, &#39;I just didn&#39;t do it because I don&#39;t care about my community,&#39;” Lyons-Bastian told me.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2015/11/how-dogs-make-friends-for-their-humans/417645/">Read: How dogs make friends for their humans</a><br><br> But when those same people were asked why they thought <em>others</em> left behind dog waste, they judged them far more harshly. “Have you heard of the fundamental attribution error?” Lyons-Bastian asked me. This is people&#39;s tendency to attribute their own actions to the environment or things otherwise out of their control, and others&#39; actions to their character.<br><br> The second part of Lyons-Bastian&#39;s survey focused on what might motivate respondents to pick up more frequently. She found the answer was not fines, nor was it scolding. Instead, it was employing the psychological concept of social proof, which suggests that people are influenced by the decisions of those around them: “If the people in your community and in your circle are doing something, you&#39;re much more likely to do it.” Conversely, if you think other people aren&#39;t doing something, it&#39;s easy to wonder why you&#39;re bothering to do it yourself.<br><br> Dominic Packer, a co-author of the book <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-power-of-us-harnessing-our-shared-identities-to-improve-performance-increase-cooperation-and-promote-social-harmony-jay-j-van-bavel/9780316538411?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>The Power of Us: Harnessing Our Shared Identities to Improve Performance, Increase Cooperation, and Promote Social Harmony</em></a> , has also found this to be true. “One of the things that motivates people to comply with the norm is a sense of identity,” he said. Messaging that New Yorkers are people who pick up after their dogs—unlike the people from all of those other loser cities—might do the trick. What does <em>not</em> work, he said, is emphasizing the number of people who are behaving badly, which suggests that behaving badly is the norm. This is unfortunate news for all of those flashy press conferences.<br><br> For a city with an estimated 500,000 dogs, compliance in New York is evidently great. No matter how annoyed New Yorkers might be at the sight of stray feces, they must admit that they are not encountering it at a rate of half a million times a day. Maybe instead of a sign scolding those few dog owners who ruin it for everyone else, what would <em>really</em> be helpful is a sign that says: <span class="smallcaps">ISN&#39;T IT WONDERFUL HOW WE&#39;RE ALL PICKING UP POOP?</span><br><br> Though many attribute the perceived increase in dog waste to the pandemic, which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2022/01/07/covid-dogs-return-to-work/">appeared</a> to temporarily cause an increase in dog purchase and adoption, Julie Menin, the city councilmember, thinks the problem is, in fact, sign-related: the product of the city removing its dilapidated <span class="smallcaps">curb your dog</span> signs in 2013 and not replacing them with new ones. “The expectation was that people would clean up after their dogs” without the signs, she said. “But that just proved not to be the case.”<br><br> Menin launched a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abc7ny.com/curb-your-dog-design-contest-waste-winner/13377498/">contest</a> for residents to design a new sign, which she plans to hang up across her district. The winner was announced on June 12: a cartoon image of a doggy Statue of Liberty holding a bone and a shovel, with the slogan, <span class="smallcaps">Clean streets for all. Pick up after your pup!</span> Not as good as my sign suggestion, but still cute.<br><br> I asked whether she thought anything below 100 percent compliance would be acceptable to her complaining  constituents, and she didn&#39;t answer, instead emphasizing that “it really can&#39;t get worse than it is now.” (Unfortunately this is in direct conflict with a central law of universe: “It can always get worse.”)<br><br> I don&#39;t think that expecting cities to be completely free of dog waste is reasonable, nor do I believe that human inconsiderateness can be legislated away entirely. There will always be outliers: those without a bag, those who genuinely did not notice what their dog was doing, those with other complicating factors that we are not privy to. And there will, of course, always be assholes. The problem is intractable because humans are imperfect.<br><br> So though it&#39;s natural to focus on the poop you just stepped in, it might be healthier (and more effective) to put a greater focus on all the dog waste you never encounter in the first place. Most dog owners are out there doing their neighborly scooping, and they&#39;re just as annoyed as you are by those who aren&#39;t. Band together with those people to say, “Yes, here in [the place in which you live] we proudly clean up after our dogs … unlike that loser city Seattle!”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/new-york-picking-up-dog-poop/674825/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/new-york-picking-up-dog-poop/674825/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Moralism Is Ruining Cultural Criticism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The left has embraced an approach long favored by the evangelical right. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1CriJUMaNciOGkNSpMn36lYdM60=/0x0:3600x2025/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/OPR_Tsr1Sht4_RGB_2_copy/original.jpg" alt="原子弹云与男人剪影" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Universal Pictures</figcaption></figure> When I was growing up in a conservative evangelical community, one of the top priorities was to manage children&#39;s consumption of art. The effort was based on a fairly straightforward aesthetic theory: Every artwork has a clear message, and consuming messages that conflict with Christianity will harm one&#39;s faith. Helpfully, there was a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9CeHJXasrk">song</a> whose lyrics consisted precisely of this aesthetic theory: “Input Output.”<br><br><p> Input, output,<br> What goes in is what comes out.<br> Input, output,<br> That is what it&#39;s all about.<br> Input, output,<br> Your mind is a computer whose<br> Input, output daily you must choose.</p> The search for the “inputs” of secular artwork sometimes took a paranoid form—such as the belief in subliminal messages recorded in reverse, or in isolated frames from <i>Lion King</i> where smoke allegedly forms the word <i>sex</i> . Most often, however, the analysis was more direct. Portraying a behavior or describing a belief, unless accompanied immediately by a clear negative judgment, is an endorsement and a recommendation, and people who consume such messages will become more likely to behave and believe in that way.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/12/evangelical-christian/418236/">Read: Defining <em>evangelical</em></a><br><br> This theory underwrote the whole edifice of Christian contemporary music, which aimed to replace a particularly powerful avenue for negative messages. One of my running jokes for many years has been that all Top 40 music is effectively Christian contemporary music now; <i>American Idol</i> confirmed the hegemony of the “praise band” vocal style. More clear is the fact that all mainstream criticism—especially of film and television—is evangelical in form, if not in content. Every artwork is imagined to have a clear message; the portrayal of a given behavior or belief is an endorsement and a recommendation; consumption of artwork with a given message will directly result in the behaviors or beliefs portrayed. This is one of the few phenomena where the “both sides” cliché is true: Left-wing critics are just as likely to do this as their right-wing opponents. For every video of a right-wing provocateur like <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ynU-wVdesr0&amp;pp=ygUfYmVuIHNoYXBpcm8gYmFyYmllIG1vdmllIHJldmlldw%3D%3D">Ben Shapiro</a> decrying the woke excesses of <i>Barbie</i> , there is a review praising the Mattel product tie-in as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/jul/23/barbie-review-greta-gerwig-margot-robbie-ryan-riotous-candy-coloured-feminist-fable">a feminist fable</a> .<br><br> Here, however, I am more concerned with the critical practices of my comrades on the left. Among leftist publications, <i>Jacobin</i> stands out for its reductive and moralizing cultural coverage. Addressing the other major movie of this past weekend, for instance, the critic Eileen Jones worried <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jacobin.com/2023/07/christopher-nolan-oppenheimer-film-review">in a recent column</a> , “If you&#39;re already convinced of the dangers of nuclear war, superseded only by the ongoing end-times series of rolling climate catastrophes that now seem more likely to kill us all, this film is going to lack a certain urgency.” Sadly, instead of an educational presentation on nuclear war, film audiences will instead find a biopic that takes some liberties with its subject&#39;s life and character for the sake of creating a Hollywood blockbuster. Jones <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jacobin.com/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-mattel-consumerism-feminism">finds</a> more to like in <i>Barbie</i> , despite “the familiar, toothless, you-go-girl pseudo-feminist pieties that Mattel has been monetizing for decades, alongside the nostalgic how-can-our-consumer-products-be-bad affirmations of Barbie as some sort of magic, wholesomely progressive uniter of generations of mothers and daughters.”<br><br> This trend is not limited to one publication. It is pervasive in online culture, above all on social media. For instance, over coffee on the morning after the epic <i>Barbenheimer</i> Friday, I learned some disturbing facts about <i>Oppenheimer</i> on Twitter. At least one viewer was worried that the film about the man who created the nuclear bomb did not include <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/anthonyocampo/status/1682406287555055618">any Japanese characters</a> . Indeed, it did not even directly portray his invention&#39;s horrific consequences. Surely this aesthetic choice was meant to minimize his actions by rendering his victims invisible. (An article in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2023/07/who-are-the-japanese-in-christopher-nolans-oppenheimer.html"><i>New York</i> magazine</a> drew attention to the same absence.) I also <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/AlisaValdesRod1/status/1682167160364494849">learned</a> that the area surrounding <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tewawomenunited.org/2023/07/oppenheimer-and-the-other-side-of-the-story">Los Alamos was actually cleared of Indigenous and Hispanic residents</a> , another bit of history that is effectively erased by the film.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-nuclear-bomb-anxiety-nightmares/674795/">John Hendrickson: <em>Oppenheimer</em> nightmares? You&#39;re not alone.</a><br><br> Let&#39;s imagine, though, that those complaints had been anticipated and addressed. Let&#39;s imagine an entire subplot of a family going about their business in Hiroshima. We get to know and like them, to relate to them as our fellow human beings. Then, shockingly, they are incinerated by a nuclear blast. One can already hear the complaints. If the family were portrayed as too morally upstanding, it would be a dehumanizing portrayal that idealizes them as perfect victims. If they had moral flaws, the film would be subtly suggesting that they deserved their fate. And either way, the film would be attacked for offering up their suffering as a spectacle for our enjoyment. The same would go for the displaced population of Los Alamos—by portraying them as passive victims with no agency, critics would surely complain, the film would be reinscribing white authority.<br><br> Obviously leftists do not have to be as paranoid in their quest for messages supportive of the status quo as Christians playing their records backwards in the hopes of finding satanic content.  And of course we are a long way from having anything like the real-world thought police of Stalinism. During that dark era of Soviet history, writers and artists were expected to subscribe to the standards of socialist realism—which, instead of portraying the sordid and brutal reality of the present, anticipated the future reality of socialism by showing heroic workers building a utopian society. Those who fell short of those ideological expectations could expect a personal phone call from Comrade Stalin, if not worse. By contrast, it seems relatively harmless to hope that films and TV shows might reflect one&#39;s own politics and to lament when they fail to do so. Yet the very fact that the demand is so open-ended that it is impossible to imagine an artwork meeting its largely unstated and unarticulated standards shows that something has gone wrong here.<br><br> To be clear, I don&#39;t want to defend <i>Oppenheimer</i> in any way. I have not actually seen the film. Nothing anyone is saying is necessarily <i>wrong</i> ; it&#39;s just <i>not interesting</i> . Like most film and TV viewers, I read reviews because I want to decide whether or not to see a given movie or show, or else to think it through from a fresh perspective. For example, I note that <i>Oppenheimer</i> is very long—how is the pacing? Does it maintain a clear focus throughout, or does it indulge the common vice of biopics by trying to cram too much in? The type of critical literature that concerns me does not address such basic aesthetic questions, or does so only incidentally.<br><br> Even more insidiously, though, the logical goal of such very narrow standards could be to create artwork that is straightforward political propaganda. We&#39;ve seen how badly that turned out for the evangelicals (and, indeed, for the Stalinists). Even if we are unlikely to face the scourge of a Leninist equivalent to <i>VeggieTales</i> , however, this style of criticism infantilizes its audience members by assuming they are essentially ideology-processing machines—unlike the wise commentator who somehow manages to see through the deception.<br><br> Political problems cannot be solved on the aesthetic level. And it&#39;s much more likely that people are consuming politics as a kind of aesthetic performance or as a way of expressing aesthetic preferences than that they are somehow reading their politics off <i>Succession</i> , for example (“Welp, I guess rich people are good now. Better vote Republican!”). Just as the reduction of art to political propaganda leads to bad art, the aestheticization of politics leads to bad, irresponsible politics. That&#39;s because aesthetics and politics are not the same thing. They are not totally unrelated, obviously, but they are also and even primarily <i>different</i> . A political message <i>can</i> be part of an aesthetic effect, just as a political movement can benefit from an aesthetic appeal. But we get nowhere if we confuse or collapse these categories.<br><br> <small><i>This story was adapted from a post on Adam Kotsko&#39;s blog,</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://itself.blog/2023/07/22/we-are-all-evangelicals-now-a-nuclear-take/"><i>An Und Für Sich</i></a> <i>.</i></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-moralizing-reviews-social-media/674823/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-moralizing-reviews-social-media/674823/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[America Already Has an AI Underclass]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Search engines, ChatGPT, and other AI tools wouldn&#39;t function without an army of contractors. Now those workers say they&#39;re underpaid and mistreated. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/W9dDOpfZoxUtGyb25U2I5MMXY_M=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/24/ai_rater_f_3/original.jpg" alt="一只机械手投射出人头形状的阴影。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Joanne Imperio / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> O <span class="smallcaps">n weekdays, between homeschooling</span> her two children, Michelle Curtis logs on to her computer to squeeze in a few hours of work. Her screen flashes with Google Search results, the writings of a Google chatbot, and the outputs of other algorithms, and she has a few minutes to respond to each—judging the usefulness of the blue links she&#39;s been provided, checking the accuracy of an AI&#39;s description of a praying mantis, or deciding which of two chatbot-written birthday poems is better. She never knows what she will have to assess in advance, and for the AI-related tasks, which have formed the bulk of her work since February, she says she has little guidance and not enough time to do a thorough job.<br><br> Curtis is an AI rater. She works for the data company Appen, which is subcontracted by Google to evaluate the outputs of the tech giant&#39;s AI products and search algorithm. Countless people do similar work around the world for Google; the ChatGPT-maker, OpenAI; and other tech <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/features/23764584/ai-artificial-intelligence-data-notation-labor-scale-surge-remotasks-openai-chatbots">firms</a> . Their human feedback plays a crucial role in developing chatbots, search engines, social-media feeds, and targeted-advertising systems—the most important parts of the digital economy.<br><br> Curtis told me that the job is grueling, underpaid, and poorly defined. Whereas Google has a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://static.googleusercontent.com/media/guidelines.raterhub.com/en/searchqualityevaluatorguidelines.pdf">176-page guide</a> for search evaluations, the instructions for AI tasks are relatively sparse, she said. For every task she performs that involves rating AI outputs, she is given a few sentences or paragraphs of vague, even convoluted instructions and as little as just a few minutes to fully absorb them before the time allotted to complete the task is up. Unlike a page of Google results, chatbots promise authoritative answers—offering the final, rather than first, step of inquiry, which Curtis said makes her feel a heightened moral responsibility to assess AI responses as accurately as possible. She dreads these timed tasks for the very same reason: “It&#39;s just not humanly possible to do in the amount of time that we&#39;re given.” On Sundays, she works a full eight hours. “Those long days can really wear on you,” she said.<br><br> Armughan Ahmad, Appen&#39;s CEO, told me through a spokesperson that the company “complies with minimum wages” and is investing in improved training and benefits for its workers; a Google spokesperson said Appen is solely responsible for raters&#39; working conditions and job training. For Google to mention these people at all is notable. Despite their importance to the generative-AI boom and tech economy more generally, these workers are almost never referenced in tech companies&#39; prophecies about the ascendance of intelligent machines. AI moguls describe their products as forces akin to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/ai-gpt4-technology-analogy/673509/">electricity</a> or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/31/technology/sam-altman-open-ai-chatgpt.html">nuclear fission</a> , like facts of nature waiting to be discovered, and speak of “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/elon-musks-ai-firm-xai-launches-website-2023-07-12/">maximally curious</a> ” machines that learn and grow on their own, like children. The human side of sculpting algorithms tends to be relegated to opaque descriptions of “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.meta.com/resources/models-and-libraries/llama/">human annotations</a> ” and “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.google.com/search/howsearchworks/how-search-works/rigorous-testing/#qualityTests">quality tests</a> ,” evacuated of the time and energy powering those annotations.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/google-search-generative-experience-content-creation/674674/">Read: Google&#39;s new search tool could eat the internet alive</a><br><br> The tech industry has a history of veiling the difficult, exploitative, and sometimes dangerous work needed to clean up its platforms and programs. But as AI rapidly infiltrates our daily lives, tensions between tech companies framing their software as self-propelling and the AI raters and other people actually pushing those products along have started to surface. In 2021, Appen raters began organizing with the Alphabet Workers Union-Communications Workers of America to push for greater recognition and compensation; Curtis joined its ranks last year. At the center of the fight is a big question: In the coming era of AI, can the people doing the tech industry&#39;s grunt work ever be seen and treated not as tireless machines but simply as what they are—human?<br><br> T <span class="smallcaps">he technical name</span> for the use of such ratings to improve AI models is <em>reinforcement learning with human feedback</em> , or RLHF. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/research/instruction-following">OpenAI</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.deepmind.com/blog/building-safer-dialogue-agents">Google</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www-files.anthropic.com/production/images/Model-Card-Claude-2.pdf">Anthropic</a> , and other companies all use the technique. After a chatbot has processed massive amounts of text, human feedback helps fine-tune it. ChatGPT is impressive because using it feels like chatting with a human, but that pastiche does not naturally arise through ingesting data from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/artificial-intelligence-ai-chatgpt-dall-e-2-learning/672754/">something like the entire internet</a> , an amalgam of recipes and patents and blogs and novels. Although AI programs are set up to be effective at pattern detection, they “don&#39;t have any sense of contextual understanding, no ability to parse whether AI-generated text looks more or less like what a human would have written,” Sarah Myers West, the managing director of the AI Now Institute, an independent research organization, told me. Only an actual person can make that call.<br><br> The program might write multiple recipes for chocolate cake, which a rater ranks and edits. Those evaluations and examples will inform the chatbot&#39;s statistical model of language and next-word predictions, which should make the program better at writing recipes in the style of a human, for chocolate cake and beyond. A person might check a chatbot&#39;s response for factual accuracy, rate how well it fits the prompt, or flag toxic outputs; subject experts can be particularly helpful, and they tend to be paid more.<br><br> Using human evaluations to improve algorithmic products is a fairly old practice at this point: Google and Facebook have been using them for almost a decade, if not more, to develop <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://support.google.com/websearch/answer/9281931">search engines</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.facebook.com/business/help/204798856225114?id=649869995454285">targeted ads</a> , and other products, Sasha Luccioni, an AI researcher at the machine-learning company Hugging Face, told me. The extent to which human ratings have shaped today&#39;s algorithms depends on who you ask, however. Major tech companies that design and profit from search engines, chatbots, and other algorithmic products tend to characterize the raters&#39; work as only one among many important aspects of building cutting-edge AI products. Courtenay Mencini, a Google spokesperson, told me that “ratings do not directly impact or solely train our algorithms. Rather, they&#39;re one data point … taken in aggregate with extensive internal development and testing.” OpenAI has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/research/gpt-4">emphasized</a> that training on huge amounts of text, rather than RLHF, accounts for most of GPT-4&#39;s capabilities.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/">From the September 2023 issue: Does Sam Altman know what he&#39;s creating?</a><br><br> AI experts I spoke with outside these companies took a different stance. Targeted human feedback has been “the single most impactful change that made [current] AI models as good as they are,” allowing the leap from GPT-2&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/7/20953040/openai-text-generation-ai-gpt-2-full-model-release-1-5b-parameters">half-baked</a> emails to GPT-4&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/open-ai-gpt4-chatbot-technology-power/673421/">convincing essays</a> , Luccioni said. She and others argue that tech companies intentionally downplay the importance of human feedback. Such obfuscation “sockets away some of the most unseemly elements of these technologies,” such as hateful content and misinformation that humans have to identify, Myers West told me—not to mention the conditions the people work under. Even setting aside those elements, describing the extent of human intervention would risk dispelling the magical and marketable illusion of intelligent machines—a “ <em>Wizard of Oz</em> effect,” Luccioni said.<br><br> Despite tech companies&#39; stated positions, digging into their own press statements and research papers about AI reveals that they frequently do acknowledge the value of this human labor, if in broad terms. A Google blog post promoting a new chatbot last year, for instance, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.deepmind.com/blog/building-safer-dialogue-agents">said</a> that “to create safer dialogue agents, we need to be able to learn from human feedback.” Google has similarly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blog.google/products/search/raters-experiments-improve-google-search/">described</a> human evaluations as necessary to its search engine. The company touts RLHF as “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/google-cloud-launches-new-ai-models-opens-generative-ai-studio">particularly useful</a> ” for applying its AI services to industries such as health care and finance. Two lead researchers at OpenAI similarly described human evaluations as vital to training ChatGPT in an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/03/03/1069311/inside-story-oral-history-how-chatgpt-built-openai/">interview</a> with <em>MIT Technology Review</em> . The company stated elsewhere that GPT-4 exhibited “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.08774.pdf">large improvements</a> ” in accuracy after RLHF training and that human feedback was crucial to fine-tuning it. Meta&#39;s most recent language model, released this week, relies on “over 1 million new human annotations,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.meta.com/resources/models-and-libraries/llama/">according to the company</a> .<br><br> To some extent, the significance of humans&#39; AI ratings is evident in the money pouring into them. One company that hires people to do RLHF and data annotation was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2023/05/09/sclae-ai-disruptor-50.html">valued</a> at more than $7 billion in 2021, and its CEO recently <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/alexandr_wang/status/1620934510820093952?lang=en">predicted</a> that AI companies will soon spend billions of dollars on RLHF, similar to their investment in computing power. The global market for labeling data used to train these models (such as tagging an image of a cat with the label “cat”), another part of the “ghost work” powering AI, could <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2022/04/20/1050392/ai-industry-appen-scale-data-labels/">reach</a> nearly $14 billion by 2030, according to an estimate from April 2022, months before the ChatGPT gold rush began.<br><br> A <span class="smallcaps">ll of that money</span> , however, rarely seems to be reaching the actual people doing the ghostly labor. The contours of the work are starting to materialize, and the few public investigations into it are alarming: Workers in Africa are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6275995/chatgpt-facebook-african-workers-union/">paid as little as $1.50 an hour</a> to check outputs for disturbing content that has reportedly left some of them with PTSD. Some contractors <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/features/23764584/ai-artificial-intelligence-data-notation-labor-scale-surge-remotasks-openai-chatbots">in the US</a> can earn only a couple of dollars above the minimum wage for repetitive, exhausting, and rudderless work. The pattern is similar to that of social-media content moderators, who can be paid a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/25/18229714/cognizant-facebook-content-moderator-interviews-trauma-working-conditions-arizona">tenth as much as software engineers</a> to scan traumatic content for hours every day. “The poor working conditions directly impact data quality,” Krystal Kauffman, a fellow at the Distributed AI Research Institute and an organizer of raters and data labelers on Amazon Mechanical Turk, a crowdsourcing platform, told me.<br><br> Stress, low pay, minimal instructions, inconsistent tasks, and tight deadlines—the sheer volume of data needed to train AI models almost necessitates a rush job—are a recipe for human error, according to Appen raters affiliated with the Alphabet Workers Union-Communications Workers of America and multiple independent experts. Documents <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-12/google-s-ai-chatbot-is-trained-by-humans-who-say-they-re-overworked-underpaid-and-frustrated">obtained</a> by <em>Bloomberg</em> , for instance, show that AI raters at Google have as little as three minutes to complete some tasks, and that they evaluate high-stakes responses, such as how to safely dose medication. Even OpenAI has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.08774.pdf">written</a> , in the technical report accompanying GPT-4, that “undesired behaviors [in AI systems] can arise when instructions to labelers were underspecified” during RLHF.<br><br> Tech companies have at times responded to these issues by stating that ratings are not the only way they check accuracy, that humans doing those ratings are paid <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/features/23764584/ai-artificial-intelligence-data-notation-labor-scale-surge-remotasks-openai-chatbots">adequately</a> based on their location and afforded proper training, and that viewing traumatic materials is not a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/25/18229714/cognizant-facebook-content-moderator-interviews-trauma-working-conditions-arizona">typical</a> experience. Mencini, the Google spokesperson, told me that Google&#39;s wages and benefits standards for contractors do not apply to raters, because they “work part-time from home, can be assigned to multiple companies&#39; accounts at a time, and do not have access to Google&#39;s systems or campuses.” In response to allegations of raters seeing offensive materials, she said that workers “select to opt into reviewing sensitive content, and can opt out freely at any time.” The companies also tend to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/06/14/google-ai-bard-raters-chatbot-accuracy/">shift blame</a> to their <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6147458/facebook-africa-content-moderation-employee-treatment/">vendors</a> —Mencini, for instance, told me that “Google is simply not the employer of any Appen workers.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/generative-ai-human-culture-philosophy/674165/">Read: The coming humanist renaissance</a><br><br> Appen&#39;s raters told me that their working conditions do not align with various tech companies&#39; assurances—and that they hold Appen and Google responsible, because both profit from their work. Over the past year, Michelle Curtis and other raters have demanded more time to complete AI evaluations, benefits, better compensation, and the right to organize. The job&#39;s flexibility does have advantages, they told me. Curtis has been able to navigate her children&#39;s medical issues; another Appen rater I spoke with, Ed Stackhouse, said the adjustable hours afford him time to deal with a heart condition. But flexibility does not justify low pay and a lack of benefits, Shannon Wait, an organizer with the AWU-CWA, told me; there&#39;s nothing flexible about precarity.<br><br> The group made headway at the start of the year, when Curtis and her fellow raters received their first-ever raise. She now makes $14.50 an hour, up from $12.75—still below the minimum of $15 an hour that Google has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://about.google/extended-workforce/">promised</a> to its vendors, temporary staff, and contractors. The union continued raising concerns about working conditions; Stackhouse wrote a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/AlphabetWorkers/status/1658489222695915522">letter</a> to Congress about these issues in May. Then, just over two weeks later, Curtis, Stackhouse, and several other raters received an email from Appen stating, “Your employment is being terminated due to business conditions.”<br><br> The AWU-CWA suspected that Appen and Google were punishing the raters for speaking out.  “The raters that were let go all had one thing in common, which was that they were vocal about working conditions or involved in organizing,” Stackhouse told me. Although Appen did suffer a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://s41256.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Appen_AR22_Interactive_v-final.pdf">drop</a> in revenue during the broader tech downturn last year, the company also had, and has, open job postings. Four weeks before the termination, Appen had sent an email offering cash incentives to work more hours and meet “a significant spike in jobs available since the beginning of year,” when the generative-AI boom was in full swing; just six days before the layoffs, Appen sent another email lauding “record-high production levels” and re-upping the bonus-pay offer. On June 14, the union filed a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nlrb.gov/case/32-CA-320053">complaint</a> with the National Labor Relations Board alleging that Appen and Google had <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/06/14/google-ai-bard-raters-chatbot-accuracy/">retaliated</a> against raters “by terminating six employees who were engaged in protected [labor] activity.”<br><br> Less than two weeks after the complaint was filed, Appen reversed its decision to fire Curtis, Stackhouse, and the others; their positions were reinstated with back pay. Ahmad, Appen&#39;s CEO, told me in an email that his company bases “employment decisions on business requirements” and is “happy that our business needs changed and we were able to hire back the laid off contributors.” He added, “Our policy is not to discriminate against employees due to any protected labor activities,” and that “we&#39;ve been actively investing in workplace enhancements like smarter training, and improved benefits.”<br><br> Mencini, the Google spokesperson, told me that “only Appen, as the employer, determines their employees&#39; working conditions,” and that “Appen provides job training for their employees.” As with compensation and training, Mencini deflected responsibility for the treatment of organizing workers as well: “We, of course, respect the labor rights of Appen employees to join a union, but it&#39;s a matter between them and their employer, Appen.”<br><br> T <span class="smallcaps">hat AI purveyors would obscure</span> the human labor undergirding their products is predictable. Much of the data that train AI models is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.noemamag.com/the-exploited-labor-behind-artificial-intelligence/">labeled by people</a> making poverty wages, many of them located in the global South. Amazon deliveries are cheap in part because <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/06/15/us/amazon-workers.html">working conditions</a> in the company&#39;s warehouses subsidize them. Social media is usable and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2022/10/28/23428132/elon-musk-twitter-acquisition-problems-speech-moderation">desirable</a> because of armies of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/social-media-companies-are-outsourcing-their-dirty-work-philippines-generation-workers-is-paying-price/">content moderators</a> also largely in the global South. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/resources/cloud-computing-dictionary/what-is-cloud-computing">“Cloud” computing</a> , a cornerstone of Amazon&#39;s and Microsoft&#39;s businesses, takes place in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.blackstone.com/insights/article/greg-blank-mike-forman-on-demand-for-data-centers/">giant data centers</a> .<br><br> AI raters might be understood as an extension of that cloud, treated not as laborers with human needs so much as productive units, carbon transistors on a series of fleshly microchips—objects, not people. Yet even microchips take up space; they require not just electricity but also ventilation to keep from overheating. The Appen raters&#39; termination and reinstatement is part of “a more generalized pattern within the tech industry of engaging in very swift retaliation against workers” when they organize for better pay or against ethical concerns about the products they work on, Myers West, of the AI Now Institute, told me.<br><br> Ironically, one crucial bit of human labor that AI programs have proved unable to automate is their own training. Human subjectivity and prejudice have long migrated their way into algorithms, and those flaws mean machines may not be able to perfect themselves. Various attempts to train AI models with other AI models have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/generative-ai-future-training-models/674478/">bred further bias</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.03277">worsened</a> performance, though a few have shown <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2305.03047.pdf">limited</a> success. “I can&#39;t imagine that we will be able to replicate [human intervention] with current AI approaches,” Hugging Face&#39;s Luccioni told me in an email; Ahmad said that “using AI to train AI can have dire consequences as it pertains to the viability and credibility of this technology.” The tech industry has so far failed to purge the ghosts haunting its many other machines and services—the people organizing on warehouse floors, walking out of corporate headquarters, unionizing overseas, and leaking classified documents. Appen&#39;s raters are proving that, even amid the generative-AI boom, humanity may not be so easily exorcized.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-chatbot-human-evaluator-feedback/674805/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-chatbot-human-evaluator-feedback/674805/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Ascendance of Girl Culture]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> <em>Barbie</em> purports to be critical of Mattel while being enthusiastically sponsored by Mattel. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/x-xsz1KnKkOjhSGRth3GJNsRuTg=/235x0:2763x1422/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/MCDBARB_WB037/original.jpg" alt="An image of Margot Robbie as Barbie" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Warner Bros.</figcaption></figure> In the 2000s, male artists routinely excavated the popular culture of their boyhood for imaginative repurposing in their art. Michael Chabon&#39;s novel <i>The Amazing Adventures of Kavalier &amp; Clay</i> traces the lives of two men who become comic-book creators. In Jonathan Lethem&#39;s <i>The</i> <i>Fortress of Solitude</i> , two boys find a magic ring they use to take on superpowers; the title itself evokes the fictional fortress of Superman. Back then, I remember feeling that the equivalent was not possible for women artists, that the popular culture of American girlhood (horses, dolls, gymnastics) was still considered silly, juvenile—impossible to recuperate as adult art worth taking seriously.<br><br> Greta Gerwig seems at last a counterexample. Her entire career as a filmmaker has, in a sense, been a campaign to make art of girlhood materials. Her 2019 film, <i>Little Women</i> , remakes the 19th-century girlhood classic, rendering it freshly urgent for a 21st-century audience. (“I&#39;ve been angry every day of my life,” Marmee, the saintly mother of the novel, says in Gerwig&#39;s version.) Her directorial debut, <i>Lady Bird</i> (2017), captures the angst of a 17-year-old girl&#39;s coming-of-age in all its granular reality, taking seriously adolescent longing and anger.<br><br> And now here is the <i>Barbie</i> juggernaut. <i>Barbie</i> dominated the box office on its opening weekend, grossing a stunning $155 million: a post-pandemic high, and the biggest opening for any feature film directed by a woman. Grown-up art about girlhood really can be an economic and cultural powerhouse. In the past week, women I barely know and women I have known for years have texted me their excitement about the film—and then shared their response, which has been in many cases the same: They <i>loved</i> watching the film, and yet more than one felt oddly disappointed by it.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">Read: Greta Gerwig&#39;s lessons from Barbie land</a><br><br> Perhaps this is because, as the critic Dana Stevens <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/culture/2023/07/barbie-movie-2023-margot-robbie-ryan-gosling-review.html">noted in <i>Slate</i></a> , <i>Barbie</i> “never completely resolves the paradox at its heart”: The movie purports to be critical of Mattel while being enthusiastically sponsored by Mattel. The constraint is so obvious that Gerwig tries to turn it into a joke. The plot hinges on the conceit that all the Barbies mistakenly believe that their existence has turned the “real” world into a feminist paradise. Gerwig knows that no one wants to watch a hectoring film about how the doll is bad for girls&#39; self-image. So she subversively jokes about the insidious side of corporate culture while visually celebrating the Barbieness of Barbie. In this way, <i>Barbie</i> really is, if not a wholly successful film, certainly a powerful monument to the strangeness of American girl culture, which remains impoverished in its vision of what young girls are and want.<br><br> At once a commercial for a toy and a delicious romp through the pleasures of childhood play, <i>Barbie</i> sits uneasily at the intersection of reality, fantasy, and critique. It is joyous, winking, frothily cinematic. There are lavish costumes, deftly choreographed dance numbers, and aesthetically sophisticated visual puns. Barbie, played by Margot Robbie, is wryly known as “Stereotypical Barbie”; blond and perfect, she showers and drinks without ever getting wet, walks on her toes, floats down from her bedroom to the street as if held by an invisible girl&#39;s hand. The script is peppered with genuinely incisive and funny skewers of gender stereotypes. A key moment in the plot involves the Barbies allowing the Kens to “sing at them” while playing guitars; the preposition is pure genius.<br><br> Like many women before it, <i>Barbie</i> tries to be many things to many people. One trailer&#39;s tag line was “If you love Barbie, this movie is for you. If you hate Barbie, this movie is for you.” The line gets at the challenge here, adjacent to the one Stevens identified: How do you make a film for an audience that remains fiercely divided about the material you&#39;re writing about?<br><br> This conflict, one might say, is precisely what forces Stereotypical Barbie out of her dreamy pink home on a quest to understand a series of strange phenomena: cellulite, cold showers, melancholy. We meet Barbie in Barbie Land, where women rule, literally. There is a Barbie president; there are nine Supreme Court Barbies. Kens are reduced to supporting roles. They wait for Barbies to kiss them, notice them, long for them. But when Barbie begins having relentless thoughts of death, she and one of the Kens, played to deliciously banal perfection by Ryan Gosling, enter “reality.” It isn&#39;t the paradise she expected; men ogle her and a girl calls her a “fascist.” As reality&#39;s reality dawns on Barbie, she articulates a set of feelings at once amusingly framed and horrifying to witness: “I feel … ill at ease,” she says. “I&#39;m getting undertones of violence.” (Cue women squirming in the audience.) Meanwhile, Ken is radicalized by his experience: He likes the attention he gets. He sees a new world, one where men are not second-class citizens, and returns to Barbie Land to brainwash the Barbies into serving the Kens. The former Supreme Court justices are now cheerleaders.<br><br> Rather than get angry at what has happened to Barbie Land, Barbie is crushed. She stops wearing makeup and lies on the floor in despair, waiting for another Barbie to take the lead in fixing her society. And so the second half of the film tells the somewhat incoherent story of her evolution from thinking she is not “good enough” to becoming a woman bent on self-determination. In reality, she befriends a real woman named Gloria (America Ferrara), who delivers an impassioned motivational speech about how hard it is to be a woman in a world that demands contradictory things: to care tirelessly for your children but not talk about them too much; to act when action seems fruitless.<br><br> The challenge that Barbie, as a cultural object, presents Gerwig is how to mine the performative pleasures of clothes and dance numbers alongside the travesties of modern American culture while framing the story as if the two are wholly disconnected. She&#39;s trying to show what it might really be like to go from a dream land to contemporary America, where <i>Roe v. Wade</i> has been overturned, parents don&#39;t automatically get parental leave after the birth of a child, and most CEOs of corporations (including Mattel) are still men.<br><br> <i>Barbie</i> is at once radical and conventional. It is radical in its light indictment of the patriarchy: One of the very best lines of cultural criticism I&#39;ve heard in ages comes when Ken says, “To be honest, when I found out the patriarchy wasn&#39;t about horses I lost interest.” (The movie might be best read as a brilliant portrait of aggrieved far-right masculinity.) It is somewhat more conventional in its vision of a dream girlhood and its idea of what Barbie <i>is</i> . And perhaps here is where Mattel&#39;s influence is strongest. Despite the presence of Doctor Barbies and Supreme Court Barbies, Gerwig&#39;s Barbies still largely conform to rigid beauty norms; a night of fun is a dance number in glittery and sexy clothes; and no conflict ever occurs, because the days are coated in a vapid gloss of fashion and pink plastic that corporate America has always been selling girls. This is the vision that led my second-wave-feminist mother to ban Barbie from our house. When my aunt gave me two for my fifth birthday, they mysteriously disappeared a few days later.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">Read: The surprising key to understanding the Barbie film</a><br><br> To some degree, this vapidity is Gerwig&#39;s point: Barbie must leave Barbie Land, as all girls must, to confront a messier and more complex reality. And yet <i>Barbie</i> skirts the deep cognitive dissonance the doll inspires in many girls. Thanks to my mother&#39;s ban, I played with Barbie only at friends&#39; houses. I recall finding the doll boring, because she was relentlessly tethered to <i>our</i> world and to the culture&#39;s expectations for adult me, ones that didn&#39;t yet interest me (boys, houses, Malibu). Instead of playing Barbie, my friends and I disfigured her so she looked like the film&#39;s Weird Barbie (Kate MacKinnon), a doll with a 1980s punk haircut who&#39;s out of step with all the others. Like the montage in the film showing what a girl did to Weird Barbie, we chopped off the doll&#39;s hair down to chunky sprouts, turned her head backward, covered her face in green marker. In the film&#39;s lingo, Weird Barbie is weird because girls have “played too hard” with her, a telling evasion. Weird Barbie is not weird because someone played too hard with her. Weird Barbie is weird, as Gerwig surely knows, because some girl used her to express all her frustration at the confection of materialism and reductive beauty norms. Weird Barbie wants to raze Barbie Land, not just help Stereotypical Barbie see reality for what it is.<br><br> <i>Barbie</i> is a fascinating moment in the ascendance of girl culture, a brilliantly twisty dive into the core of the contradictory scripts shaping what it is like to grow up as a girl in America. One of those scripts teaches that girlhood isn&#39;t a space of imaginative autonomy but a kind of prep school for a conventional consumer adulthood that will be shaped by hair appointments, shopping, and a job. Despite the constraints she faces, Gerwig tries to invoke a more capacious script for girlhood at the film&#39;s end, in a beautiful montage of girls playing around the world, in muted visuals that starkly contrast with the Technicolor Barbie world. If the film emerges aesthetically scathed, that doesn&#39;t mean it is a failure. I left delighted by how much Gerwig had achieved through humor, and by the conviction that <i>Barbie</i> can only help make room for more films by women about women. The film&#39;s tag line is right. One can hate Barbie and still be glad this movie was made, because here it is at last: a movie full of jokes for us, the women and girls in the room. In that sense, nothing about <i>Barbie</i> is silly or juvenile.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-girlhood-greta-gerwig/674821/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-girlhood-greta-gerwig/674821/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Hollywood’s Huge 'Barbenheimer' Fumble]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>不利用<em>芭比</em>和<em>奥本海默</em>的成功将是一个灾难性的错误。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EUX8yR9vjF41FgcqK_HEtBDAZ2M=/1x0:4801x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/barbie_strikes_hr/original.jpg" alt="罢工者在“芭比”电影海报下游行。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>马里奥·塔玛/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>好莱坞的记忆力一直很差。行业分析师将在数月内预测电影未来的厄运，然后在新上映的影片超出预期时欢欣鼓舞。今年夏天也不例外： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/06/the-flash-production-issues-muschietti/674334/"><em>《闪电侠》</em></a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/06/indiana-jones-and-the-dial-of-destiny-review/674509/"><em>《夺宝奇兵》</em></a>等几部大片表现不佳， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2023/07/04/2023-movie-box-office-needs-strong-second-half-after-inconsistent-start.html">人们</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/film/news/disney-box-office-failures-indiana-jones-elemental-ant-man-1235660409/">很快就陷入了</a>绝望。但上周末带来了巨大的转变，这要归功于<em>《巴本海默》</em> ——格蕾塔·葛韦格饰演的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/"><em>芭比娃娃</em></a>和克里斯托弗·诺兰饰演的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-review-christopher-nolan/674749/"><em>奥本海默</em></a>的正面交锋。这两部电影是完全不同的、由导演主导的作品，它们使各自的预期票房翻了一番，并共同推动了历史上第四高的首周末票房。夏天可以拯救了！然而，随着演员和编剧的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">罢工</a>持续不断，制片厂似乎几乎一心要粉碎任何真正的行业发展势头的机会。<br><br>让<em>芭比</em>与<em>奥本海默</em>对抗的策略最初似乎很冒险。但葛韦格的亮粉色名牌喜剧与诺兰的 R 级三小时传记史诗之间的差异也引发了炒作。最终， <em>《芭比娃娃》</em>的首映票房为 1.62 亿美元， <em>《奥本海默》</em>的首映票房为 8200 万美元——前者创下了女性导演电影的票房纪录，而诺兰则获得了非蝙蝠侠电影史上最大的周末票房收入。<br><br>在经历了几个月商业上平淡无奇的续集之后，这对电影业来说是一个巨大的、令人振奋的成功。最重要的是，这清楚地表明观众渴望优质产品。大片并没有过时，但电影公司不能仅仅依赖最新的系列作品；一些老牌公司（例如 DC 漫画和<em>速度与激情</em>）开始失去光彩。<em>芭比</em>和<em>奥本海默</em>通过获得积极评价和提供真正引人注目的东西赢得了观众的热情：<em>芭比</em>在人群中非常有趣和快乐；<em>奥本海默的</em>视觉效果令人惊叹，并在 IMAX 等大型优质银幕上提升了其销量。这两部电影都获得了 A 级 CinemaScore，这是口碑的良好指标，因此整个 8 月份的票房应该会保持健康。<br><br>尽管如此，麻烦即将来临，第一个例子也出现在上周末。由<em>赞</em>达亚主演的浪漫网球喜剧《挑战者》 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/zendaya-challengers-actors-strike-release-date-1235444723/">将上映日期</a>从9月15日改为明年4月26日，取消了原定在威尼斯电影节上映的计划。这部电影由卢卡·瓜达格尼诺（《<em>请以你的名字呼唤我</em>》）执导，本来打算在米高梅的影院大肆宣传，但演员工会罢工意味着赞达亚和她的联合主演可能无法宣传这部电影，这会给依赖明星力量的项目带来困难。<br><br>其他几个项目也因罢工而被推迟，包括 A24 的独立喜剧<em>《Problemista》</em> 、狮门影业的励志剧<em>《白鸟》</em>和<em>《辣身舞》</em>续集。但接下来真正的多米诺骨牌可能会倒下，有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/film/news/dune-2-release-date-change-2024-warner-bros-strike-1235676007/">传言</a>称华纳兄弟可能会将其即将上映的大片<em>——《沙丘第二部》</em> 、 <em>《紫色》</em>和<em>《海王与失落的王国</em>》——从 2023 年的日历中剔除。计划于秋季上映的其他大片包括马丁·斯科塞斯的<em>《花月杀手》</em> 、超级英雄电影<em>《奇迹》</em>和《<em>饥饿游戏》</em>前传，所有这些都需要明星在新闻发布会上来推动其销售。 （<em>芭比</em>和<em>奥本海默</em>的演员们在罢工之前接受了许多媒体采访。）<br><br>危机不仅正在酝酿，而且还在酝酿之中。它在这里。电影制片厂不与美国演员工会和美国作家协会恢复谈判的每一天都会危及好莱坞的未来。新冠疫情造成的连年延误加剧了人们对电影的生存焦虑：更多的电影被分发到流媒体服务，观众也习惯了在家观看新上映的电影。现在人们又可以放心地去看电影了，<em>巴本海默</em>现象正在提醒各个年龄段的观众，大银幕体验的价值。不利用这种能量将是一个灾难性的错误。<br><br>然而，这似乎是电影和电视制片人联盟（代表主要制片厂的松散贸易协会）愿意犯的错误。 WGA 已经罢工 84 天，没有迹象表明短期内会恢复谈判。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/writers-strike-hollywood-studios-deal-fight-wga-actors-1235434335/"><em>Deadline 的</em>一篇文章</a>援引一位匿名“顶级制片人”的话说，制片厂将允许僵局至少持续到十月。 AMPTP 予以反击，声称其“致力于达成协议”。不管怎样，这篇报道强调了 WGA 和制片厂之间的关系已经变得多么有害。残差、生成人工智能的使用以及流数据的共享都是重要的分歧点。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">阅读：商人打破了好莱坞</a><br><br>多年来，娱乐业经历了多次 WGA 罢工，但 SAG 的行动更令人惊讶，并且立即产生了影响，基本上关闭了所有主要电影制作并影响了未来的上映时间表。许多相同的问题，特别是流媒体残差和人工智能，在两组谈判中都处于危险之中，这可能就是为什么 AMPTP 不愿意与 SAG 快速讨价还价的原因——它知道 WGA 可以利用这一点作为杠杆。相反，好莱坞大佬们似乎陷入了死亡漩涡，除了对工会和他们自己施加惩罚之外，不知道如何推动达成协议。<br><br>在这一点上，解决罢工问题的任何拖延对电影业来说都可能是世界末日。如果电影公司将谈判推迟数月，试图迫使工会陷入绝望，那么这些电影公司的产品最终将被电影院扣留，整体票房收入将直线下降，而这可能是好莱坞达到大流行前水平的最佳机会成功的喜悦将会溜走。是的， <em>《芭比娃娃》</em>和<em>《奥本海默》</em>将继续售票，八月份的几部动作片（ <em>《忍者神龟</em>》、 <em>《巨齿鲨 2</em> 》）应该会取得一定的成功，但目前所有关于票房的公司都将很快就忘记了。好莱坞刚刚得到了自 2019 年以来最明确的确认：电影仍然可以吸引现场观众。继续释放它们是个好主意。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 20:45:43 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbenheimer-movie-theaters-hollywood-strikes/674822/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbenheimer-movie-theaters-hollywood-strikes/674822/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Greta Gerwig’s Lessons From Barbie Land]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> “你对你感兴趣的东西感兴趣，而我对女人感兴趣。” <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/HQCGi0UhG3lSR1FkaVTU_9EwfVQ=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/25/greta_gerwig_1/original.jpg" alt="格蕾塔·葛韦格的黑白肖像，双手捧着脸" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔迪·罗加克 / Trunk Archive</figcaption></figure><strong><em>本文包含电影</em></strong><strong>《芭比娃娃》的剧透<em>。</em></strong><br><br>当我问起有关肯的问题时，我与格蕾塔·葛韦格的电话就挂断了。当<em>《芭比娃娃》</em>的编剧兼导演回来时，她不知道发生了什么。我建议，<em>仅仅</em>提及肯——瑞恩·高斯林扮演的那个憔悴且被忽视的娃娃——当然会导致某种失败。葛韦格同意了。 “世界就像，<em>我不在乎</em>，”她开玩笑说。<br><br>但全世界都非常关心他所出演的电影。自周五上映以来， <em>《芭比娃娃》的</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/24/1189760422/barbie-oppenheimer-box-office-ticket-sales">表现超出了预期</a>，成为第一部首周末票房超过 1 亿美元的工作室喜剧，并创下北美首映票房最高纪录。一位女导演。观众——其中许多人从头到脚都穿着粉红色——挤满了剧院，据报道甚至导致剧院到周六晚上就<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/23/movies/barbie-oppenheimer-box-office-numbers.html">没有优惠了</a>。<br><br> <em>《芭比娃娃</em>》的大规模首映使这部电影成为葛韦格作为导演迄今为止最成功的票房作品。然而，这部电影完全符合葛韦格的全部作品：就像 2017 年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/11/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-review/544721/"><em>《伯德小姐</em></a>》和 2019 年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/greta-gerwigs-little-women-finally-gives-amy-her-due/603886/"><em>《小妇人》</em></a>一样，它深入思考了如何表达女性气质。葛韦格与搭档诺亚·鲍姆巴赫 (Noah Baumbach) 共同创作的<em>《芭比娃娃》的分量</em>可能出乎意料地沉重。在闪闪发光的服装和盛大派对的背后是一个可爱的人文主义故事，它研究产品如何影响和反映我们是谁。<br><br>也许这听起来很崇高，但考虑一下芭比（玛格特·罗比饰）和肯在现实世界中的冒险，这在电影中不仅仅是鱼出水狂欢的机会。两人肩负着在一个对待男性和女性不同的社会中生存的艰巨任务：芭比作为一个代表理想女性的玩具，与她有缺陷的目的作斗争；肯（Ken）是专为芭比娃娃的手臂糖果而创造的，他通过观察人类第一次尝到了力量的滋味，并误解了他所看到的。<em>芭比娃娃</em>既顽皮又深思熟虑，充满笑话，常常超现实的奇观包裹着真诚、女权主义和彻底的葛韦格风格的核心。<br><br>然而，当我们周五早上交谈时，葛韦格并不知道<em>芭比娃娃</em>会如何着陆。正如她所说，她预计自己会“整天焦虑不安”，并且渴望聊天，而不是担心电影的反响。我们讨论了她电影中的主题，以及她在芭比乐园的经历教会了她什么。 （别担心，Ken 的粉丝们。我们最终会找到他的。）<br><br><em>为了篇幅和清晰度，本次对话已被编辑。</em><br><br><strong>雪莉·李：</strong>这部<em>芭比娃娃</em>电影中有很多关于自我价值的重要想法，以及我们消费的东西（或者玩玩偶的东西）如何影响我们成为什么样的人。我注意到一个小女孩在放映时问了很多问题；她似乎对那些令人兴奋的主题感到有点困惑，但玩得很开心，尤其是当娃娃们唱歌跳舞时。所以我很好奇：当你和诺亚写这部电影时，你把谁想象成你的观众？<br><br><strong>格蕾塔·葛韦格：</strong>我并没有强烈的感觉，<em>这是给孩子们的东西；这是给孩子们看的。这是成人的东西</em>。我知道有些东西更令人兴奋，但当我回顾小时候的观看经历时，往往那些超出我范围的东西是最引人注目的，因为它们感觉就像一扇小窗户，让我进入了我所看到的世界。正在兴起。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>比如什么？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>这是一个非常奇怪、非常具体的记忆，但当我五岁的时候，我爸爸在纽约工作，我和妈妈得到了去<em>吉普赛</em>的加急票。我大部分都听不懂，但是当吉普赛<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wErVF7QwIY&amp;ab_channel=ProjectUnleash">在滑稽俱乐部表演</a>时，这些脱衣舞娘穿着闪闪发光的老式脱衣舞服装，我很喜欢。我不明白发生了什么，但我们得到了一本很大的纪念书，我记得只是研究了所有脱衣舞娘所在的页面，因为我认为它们是<em>如此</em>美丽。我没有任何感觉他们被客观化了。我只是喜欢他们穿着这些漂亮、闪闪发光的衣服和大头饰。我可能有很多这样的回忆。<br><br><strong>李：</strong> <em>《伯德小姐》</em>是根据你自己的经历写的， <em>《小妇人</em>》是你从小就喜欢看的书，小时候也玩过芭比娃娃。用你的电影来重温童年的试金石对你来说是一个有意的选择吗？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>老实说，在制作它们的过程中，我一直隐藏着一些东西，因为从表面上看，它们看起来很不同。但现在我看完了这个，我发现他们都在围绕着这个想法。 [<em>笑。</em> 】 你对你感兴趣的东西感兴趣，我对女人感兴趣。但我也认为——这听起来有点愚蠢——我的一个痴迷，可以说是，我真的有点不敢相信我们生活在线性时间里。 [<em>笑。</em> ] 这真是令人震惊。显然，当你有一个孩子时，你会与这个孩子紧密相连，但你在生活中也可以与它相连。<br><br>我认为，在试图将它们整合在一起并了解你现在在哪里以及你曾经去过哪里的过程中，总是会感到<em>痛苦</em>。显然，这就是我改编<em>《小妇人》</em>的方式，因为我突然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/greta-gerwigs-little-women-finally-gives-amy-her-due/603886/">以一种我年轻时从未见过的方式将这些角色视为</a>成年人。 <em>《伯德小姐》</em>是一个关于一名高中生的故事，有些事情你觉得很重要，比如舞会，但实际上这是关于你的母亲和你的<em>离开</em>。这是我回归的话题，因为无论如何，电影本质上就是一个时间胶囊，所以它已经及时处理了。这就是我在智力和艺术上感兴趣的东西，而媒介本身似乎已经嵌入了这一点。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/greta-gerwigs-little-women-finally-gives-amy-her-due/603886/">阅读：格蕾塔·葛韦格的<em>《小妇人》</em>终于给了艾米应得的</a><br><br><strong>李：</strong>也许更好的说法是：你的电影都是关于女孩如何学习成为女人的。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>哦，<em>是的</em>！<br><br><strong>李：</strong>我是不是把事情想得太简单了？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>不，我喜欢它！那好美丽。 [<em>笑。</em> ] 不过，也许这就是你永远要做的事情。我不知道那是你到达的地方。这当然与年龄无关，因为它永远在展开。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>那么，你对少女时代最关心的是什么，拍这些电影也许可以帮助你理解？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>嗯，把它拆开是很困难的，但对我来说，这很大程度上与代际对话有关。当我想到我的祖母、我的母亲、我的时候，女性的生活已经发生了如此巨大的变化，我不知道接下来会发生什么变化，但我们不断互相学习。再过一周我就满 40 岁了，我开始以一种美妙的方式感觉到，我属于年轻女性回望的那一代，这种感觉美妙又奇怪。我确实认为这是一种让我能够深入地参与对话的方式，让我感觉值得拥有，无论是女性气质、人格还是线性时间中的存在。 [<em>笑。</em> ] 线性时间是我真正的一个难题。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>你说过制作这部电影就像你制作的任何其他电影一样个人化。有没有一个场景让你觉得这部电影对你来说非常个人化？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>从<em>芭比娃娃</em>徽标的字体（我一直被泡泡字母版本所吸引，部分原因是我在玩具“反”斗城看到的那个字体）到凯特·麦金农（Kate McKinnon）的角色非常重要这一事实，一切都包罗万象。反映了我拥有的芭比娃娃，一个被人喜爱的娃娃，但在盒子里不再处于原始完美的状态。芭比在长凳上看到的那个女人是我的朋友，杰出的服装设计师安·罗斯。我一直在思考面孔，当你看着她的面孔时，我想你看到了一种感觉就像是一种生活，而那个年龄不仅在其持续时间上有价值。<br><br> [当芭比娃娃和她的创造者牵手时]，所有这些视频剪辑都是从所有参与这部电影的人那里拍摄的——女性、母亲、姐妹、女儿、朋友。我坚信，即使你不知道电影中的内容，我认为你也能感受到它们。我一直很喜欢在<em>《好家伙》</em>中，马丁·斯科塞斯的母亲扮演妈妈。你不知道那是他的妈妈，但你觉得她就是那个人，而且感觉很私人。在某种程度上，这与一个孩子看电影时无法理解每一个参考内容，但以某种方式<em>感受到</em>它并没有什么不同。其中嵌入的个人信息是人们无意识收集的一部分。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>说到那些视频片段，我们再谈谈结局。你能告诉我关于让芭比娃娃和肯夫妇达成的决定吗？这不是一个最终的解决方案，而是一种缓和的方式？伊萨·雷饰演的芭比总统不允许肯在最高法院任职。他们还在想办法。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>我们<em>都</em>还在想办法——这只是其中的一部分。但我唯一能给任何人的就是他们仍然处于混乱之中。也许这对肯斯来说会好一点。你不想告诉人们如何观看事物，但在电影的结尾，制作设计将肯的一些迷恋融入了芭比乐园。就像，完美​​并不像开始将所有东西混合在一起那样美丽。我记得当我们去拍摄结局时，当我们都走在片场时，我们就像，<em>这是有史以来最美丽的</em>。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>你能告诉我为什么肯最终拒绝父权制吗？有趣的是，他承认他不明白。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong> [<em>沉默</em>]<br><br><strong>李：</strong>哦，不。格蕾塔，我失去你了吗？你好？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>嗨，好吧，我不知道发生了什么事。它就这样消失了。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>没关系。我觉得很有趣的是，一个关于肯的问题导致你挂断了电话。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong> [<em>笑。</em> ] 世界就像是，“我不在乎。”<br><br><strong>李：</strong>是的，“我们继续吧。”所以我想问：肯实际上并不想接管芭比乐园的想法从何而来？这部电影小心翼翼地将他描绘成一个被误导的反派，而不是一个怀恨在心的对手。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>嗯，在某种程度上，你会无意识地做事情，然后再将它们拼凑起来，但有一个元素让你感觉最后，你想要从自己手中被拯救出来。我猜它的黑暗反乌托邦版本是<em>《蝇王》</em> ，就像《野孩子》一样。他们是洋娃娃，但在心理上他们也是孩子。<br><br>事实上，我想到了我的继子。当他年轻的时候，他只是不睡觉。有一次，我走进他的卧室，他站在床上，把他的毛绒玩具扔来扔去，他尖叫道：“我希望有人能让我停下来！”它是如此纯粹[<em>笑</em>]，就像，实际上，他是对的！他希望有人能让他停下来。当瑞恩·高斯林和我谈论他将如何演绎结局时，我谈到了很多关于我 4 岁儿子的事情。如果他哭了，你说：“哈罗德，我们不得不离开公园，你感到不安吗？”他会说：“是啊啊，是啊啊。”就像，他承认[他的悲伤]，但即使只是这样做也<em>很难</em>，那种情感的品质。<br><br>显然，这些系统对男性来说也很糟糕。当<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">美国发表美丽的演讲</a>时，我只是在抽泣，然后我环顾四周，发现片场里每个人都在哭。男人们也在哭，因为他们有自己的演讲，他们觉得自己永远无法发表，你知道吗？他们有自己的双钢丝，这也很痛苦。其中一些结构就是，你知道，“有人让我停下来！”我想这就是肯背后的感觉。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">阅读：理解<em>芭比</em>电影的令人惊讶的关键</a><br><br><strong>李：</strong>这是一部如此庞大的电影，也是你职业生涯中压力很大的时刻。作为一个电影人，你现在掌握着很大的权力，我想问你打算用它做什么？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong> [<em>笑。</em> ]<em>我想做什么？</em>成为一名电影制片人是一件了不起的事情，因为拍电影很困难，你永远无法真正登上山顶。因为无论你接下来要制作什么，你都还没有制作过——所以你会学到关于<em>这部</em>电影你不知道的东西，你知道吗？这很困难，但这也是吸引力的一部分。但是，如果你幸运的话，你只会每两年、三年、四年拍一部电影。所以，如果你开始计算人生，你就会意识到，<em>我要做什么，拍 15 部电影？</em>你知道，不是太多。但如果我幸运的话，我就能过上一种像我希望做的任何事情一样有意义的生活。我<em>确实</em>想在 60 多岁和 70 多岁时拍电影，如果上帝愿意，也许我会在 80 多岁时拍一些极其奇怪的电影。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>既然你已经完成了大预算工作室的主力，你认为你的故事讲述会如何发展？我想你并不总是在做生活中的数学。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>我希望能够制作各种规模的电影。我喜欢拥有制作微小东西的技能，也喜欢拥有用最大的画笔绘画的技能。它总是关于什么能给你最大的创造性自由，这可能意味着不同的事情。<br><br>我也感到非常幸运，能够成长为更大的人。我在 20 多岁的时候与人共同编剧、共同导演、演过很多戏，我就是利用这些来开始执导的。 <em>《小妇人》</em>是一个中间步骤，当我想到年轻的电影制作人时，取决于你想做什么，如果你有兴趣看看它如何扩展或收缩，那么这些中级电影的制作是令人难以置信的。我非常感激我能做到这一点，因为没有它我就不可能做到<em>这一点</em>。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 18:24:05 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Oppenheimer’s Cry of Despair in The Atlantic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在美国与苏联军备竞赛开始之际，这位伟大的科学家所能做的就是祈求希望。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AjNA1aT674UuHHRmJHHbtxriWlM=/0x0:3596x2023/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/opp_atlwriter/original.jpg" alt="J·罗伯特·奥本海默抽烟" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>环球图片/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>1949 年 2 月，曼哈顿计划洛斯阿拉莫斯实验室前主任 J. 罗伯特·奥本海默 (J. Robert Oppenheimer) 在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1949/02/the-open-mind/305431/">这本杂志</a>上写下了一场可怕的失败。自从曼哈顿计划在新墨西哥州引爆第一颗原子弹以来，已经过去了近四年。爆炸向周围的山脉发出了紫色的光芒，并从沙漠地面升起一道 40,000 英尺高的火柱、烟雾和碎片。但对奥本海默来说，余辉很快就暗淡了，取而代之的是存在主义的头号宿醉。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1949/02/the-open-mind/305431/">1949 年 2 月起：J. 罗伯特·奥本海默 (J. Robert Oppenheimer) 的《开放思想》</a><br><br>克里斯托弗·诺兰的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-review-christopher-nolan/674749/">新奥本海默传记片中</a>最令人心碎的部分发生在希里安·墨菲饰演的这位伟大科学家开始经历困扰他余生的幻灭感时。当他看着两枚炸弹从他的沙漠实验室开往日本的卡车上隆隆作响时，任何认为它们的可怕威力在他控制之下的幻想都被戳破了。三位一体测试三周后，广岛遭到轰炸。在影片中，生病的奥本海默将目光从受害者毁容的照片上移开。就像诺兰的镜头一样，让人不忍直视。<br><br>奥本海默后来说，通过原子弹，物理学家开始了解罪恶。从知识之树上摘下危险的果实后，他们把自己——以及全人类——托付给了一个堕落的世界，不断遭受自我灭绝的可能性的折磨。战争刚结束时，奥本海默安慰自己，或者也许是欺骗自己，他的发明的世界末日潜力可以而且将会得到遏制，部分通过他的努力。<br><br>奥本海默有理由相信他的影响力。公众接受了他的个人传奇：出于对拥有核武器的希特勒的恐惧，他冒险进入了看不见的原子领域，并带着巨大的力量回来了，能够阻止战争感冒，让儿子回到母亲身边。他身上堆满了荣誉。在诺兰的电影中，我们看到奥本海默被争取担任一个豪华角色：普林斯顿大学高级研究所所长，阿尔伯特·爱因斯坦的学术故乡。奥本海默还担任负责向美国原子能委员会提供建议的委员会主席。 20 世纪 40 年代后半叶，他关于科学问题的言论具有非凡的严肃性。 “当然，他对原子能潜力的了解与任何活着的美国人一样多，”他在<em>《大西洋月刊》</em>上发表的文章顶部的编辑注释中写道。<br><br>他用这个巨大的声音做了什么？他反对发展威力更强大的第二代原子武器——爱德华·泰勒称之为“超级”的氢弹——部分原因是他担心这会加速与苏联的军备竞赛。他还利用自己的声望和信誉来持续努力避免军备竞赛。他帮助起草了后来演变为“巴鲁克计划”的提案，这是美国向联合国提交的一项军备控制制度。在后者的指导下，所有国家都将放弃其原子武器计划，原子能将成为全球集体财产，由联合国的中央监管机构管理，任何国家都没有否决权。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/07/us-nuclear-strategy-cold-war-russia/638441/">阅读：我们没有核战略</a><br><br>1948 年，这些提议在联合国最终失败后，奥本海默转向了<em>《大西洋月刊》</em> 。他的文章是一件令人着迷的历史文物，也是公众悲痛的表现。它的标题是“开放的思想”，阐述了奥本海默对军备控制提案反复讨论的描述。苏联领导人投了反对票，但他们的反应并非完全否定。他们一致认为，所有国​​家都应废除其原子武器计划，原子能应接受国际监督。但他们反对美国坚持在新系统投入运行之前继续其武器计划，这也许是可以理解的。他们希望哈里·杜鲁门总统首先解除武装，但他无法遵守这个条件。<br><br>在曼哈顿计划期间，奥本海默的远见能力让他失望了。无论他对原子内部结构的计算多么准确，他都错误地判断了在他和他的同事将原子内部结构分解后会发生的地缘政治后果。出于天真，或者野心的权宜盲目性，或者两者的某种结合，他可能相信在纳粹被击败后他可以停止进一步使用它，或者炸弹的可怕景象最终会导致放弃更大规模的武器和战争。<br><br> 1949 年，他明白这样的放弃是不可能的。他写道，“我们看不到任何明确的路线可以说服世界各国政府与我们一起”进行原子裁军。这一次，影响是显而易见的，而且牵涉到美国，正如奥本海默哀叹的那样，美国“采取了一些我们原本希望可能会被普遍放弃的措施作为回应”。原子弹的大规模制造正在进行，美国科学家接到明确的命令，将新物理学用于更具破坏性的武器。<br><br>奥本海默看到一场惨淡的军备竞赛正在形成，这一次他的预见被证明是准确的。几个月之内，苏联成功测试了第一颗原子弹，仅仅三年后，即 1952 年，美国引爆了一枚氢弹，其威力大约是摧毁长崎的那颗氢弹的 500 倍。几年后，苏联也效仿了这一做法，到 1967 年奥本海默去世时，两国已拥有近 4 万枚核武器，其中许多都是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ai-warfare-nuclear-weapons-strike/673780/">一触即发的</a>。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ai-warfare-nuclear-weapons-strike/673780/">阅读：永远不要给人工智能核密码</a><br><br>奥本海默知道他帮助创造了这个世界。他试图让我们的读者为它的恐怖做好准备。总的来说，他的建议是不要失去希望，并记住我们对未来的想象力是有限的。奥本海默也许对充满不确定性的量子世界感到振奋，这在他年轻时就让他着迷。他似乎从这样一种信念中汲取了力量，即人类事务的宏观世界同样是偶然的，因此我们的命运没有任何事情是注定的。<br><br>奥本海默引用了亚伯拉罕·林肯在内战三年后在巴尔的摩发表的演讲。林肯说，在那场冲突开始时，很少有人预料到“家庭奴隶制会受到很大影响”，但事实确实如此。现实是不可预测的；它会让你大吃一惊。林肯提醒奥本海默，惊喜是双向的。一个看似堕落的世界有时可能会走向道德进步。<br><br>我们以前见过这样的转变，甚至在核领域也是如此。到了 20 世纪 80 年代，巨大的核武器库似乎已成为地球上的一个事实。 1986年，苏联的弹头库存达到历史最高水平，约为4万枚，美国则超过2万枚。很少有人想到冷战即将结束。许多人也没有想到，乔治·H·W·布什和米哈伊尔·戈尔巴乔夫将在 1991 年签署《削减战略武器条约》，这是一系列非同寻常的协议中的第一项，这些协议将两国的武库规模削减到了之前规模的四分之一以下。<br><br>布什和戈尔巴乔夫明智地抓住了这一天，因为那个时代的和平及其干净的两党战略对称性被证明是短暂的。此后，核毁灭的幽灵强势回归全球集体心理。弗拉基米尔·普京在有关<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://Read:%20What%20if%20Russia%20uses%20nuclear%20weapons%20in%20Ukraine?">入侵乌克兰的</a>演讲中援引了这一点。中国已经建立了一个足以摧毁美国所有主要城市的武库。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/06/russia-ukraine-nuclear-weapon-us-response/661315/">阅读：如果俄罗斯在乌克兰使用核武器怎么办？</a><br><br>正如奥本海默深知的那样，从<em>技术</em>上讲，威胁世界的核武器库存不会在我们身边存在数十万年。在任何小型交易所都很容易成为大型交易所的战略环境中，要让大量交易所长期存在，就是在玩傻瓜游戏。没有人应该感到安全，因为七十年过去了，没有再发生核战争事件；样本量太小。<br><br>除了提出希望之外，奥本海默并没有就如何拆除他帮助悬挂在人类文明之上的达摩克利斯之剑提供太多指导。作为一个臭名昭著的花花公子和雄辩的即兴演说家，他总是被风格所吸引。在他的<em>《大西洋月刊》</em>文章中，他以更高的形式引用了这一点。他写道：“在外交政策领域，风格使我们能够在追求对我们来说至关重要的目标与尊重他人的观点、情感和愿望之间找到和谐。”这个问题可能会从另一个角度出现。”<br><br>奥本海默想到的问题是军备控制。他要求那些代表美国进行谈判的人本着开放的精神开展工作。他要求它们能够吸引坐在桌子对面的人的理性思维。他似乎相信——或者想要相信——这种风格的广泛采用可能足以启动地缘政治新的进化步骤，通过这一步骤，世界主要大国可能会达成共识，即和平是世界的根本。最高智慧。为此，他建议保持耐心。他指出，必须让时间和自然发挥作用。七十年过去了，这看起来确实是一项缓慢的工作。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 17:41:20 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/j-robert-oppenheimer-ideas-history/674814/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/j-robert-oppenheimer-ideas-history/674814/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Elon Killed the Bird]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>关于 Twitter 看似荒谬的 X 品牌重塑的三种理论<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/JZeYzwBTVyFMw8BhsJxJAECy7ms=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/twitter_X_horz/original.jpg" alt="Twitter 的鸟标志位于 X 上方" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ben Kothe / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure>五月份，埃隆·马斯克主持对 Twitter 主页进行了一次不同寻常的微妙调整。多年来，页面顶部文本框中的提示都是“发生了什么？”，这是友好地邀请用户分享他们的想法。这位亿万富翁接管八个月后，Twitter 稍微<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/mollybohannon/2023/05/12/heres-how-twitters-appearance-has-changed-under-elon-musk/?sh=76231c985f68">改变了</a>提示，以适应新政权下该平台令人费解、混乱的本质：“发生了什么事？”变成了“发生了什么事？！”<br><br>这个问题的紧迫性与过去 48 小时相比，与 Twitter 的关系最为密切，当时马斯克决定废除 17 年的品牌知名度并重新命名。这位以前被称为 Twitter 的艺术家现在是 X。<em>发生了什么事？！</em>的确。<br><br>除了简单的“没什么”之外，我对这个问题有三个答案。 （即使使用了新名称，该网站仍然与以前几乎相同；网站左上角的蓝鸟徽标现在是一个黑色的<em>X</em> ，并且......仅此而已。）这个 X 可能只是这是一个不想拥有自己的社交网络并通过诉讼迫使其购买的人的猛烈抨击，但马斯克和 Twitter（X？） 首席执行官琳达·亚卡里诺（Linda Yaccarino）希望你相信更大的事情即将到来。<br><br> <strong>1.马斯克想要建立“埃隆互联网”。</strong><br><br>第一个理论要求认真对待马斯克的野心。在去年 10 月的一条推文中，他 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1577428272056389633">宣称</a>“购买 Twitter 是创建 X 这个一切应用程序的加速剂。”这些“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vox.com/technology/2023/4/18/23687125/elon-musk-twitter-x-super-app-wechat">超级应用</a>程序”的版本已经存在，并且在亚洲、非洲和拉丁美洲很流行，所以我们知道这意味着什么：X 将作为一个整体平台，包括支付处理和银行、拼车、新闻、与朋友，还有大量的商业活动。把它想象成互联网，但不要离开马斯克的围墙花园。在 2022 年 6 月 Twitter 市政厅<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vox.com/recode/23171541/leaked-transcript-elon-musk-first-meeting-twitter-employees">泄露的</a>录音中，马斯克暗示中国的微信是 X 的某种模型。“中国以外没有微信运动，”他说。 “我认为这是一个真正的机会来创造这一点。在中国，你基本上都生活在微信上，因为它对你的日常生活非常有用，非常有帮助。我认为，如果我们能够实现这一目标，甚至通过 Twitter 接近这一目标，那将是巨大的成功。”<br><br>如果你眯起眼睛，你就能看出其中的逻辑。 Twitter 上的很多人——影响者、自由职业者、小企业主——都使用这个平台来销售东西。其中许多人使用各种“个人简介中的链接”页面来引导人们进行工作并接收付款。 X，理论上的一切应用程序，可以简化和整合这些交流，并且像微信一样，从中 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessofapps.com/data/wechat-statistics/">产生收入</a>。马斯克已经启动了一项计划，与 Twitter 的一些较大的“创建者”帐户分享广告收入，该计划的早期受益者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/07/13/twitter-creators-payments-right-wing/">包括</a>许多著名的右翼冲击运动员。如果他能够设法让数亿人在他的应用程序上生活、购物和银行，而不是发表垃圾言论并与白人民族主义者争论政治，那将是一个巨大的成功。<br><br>为此，X 需要构建一个先进、安全的支付平台；申请适当的监管许可来合法处理付款和储存资金；当然，还要招募企业和金融机构使用该平台。据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ft.com/content/9d84d534-b2dd-4cff-85d1-aee137b26a45"><em>英国《金融时报》报道</em></a>，该公司于今年年初开始提交这些许可证的申请，并一直在建设部分支付基础设施。坏消息是，马斯克负责牵头该项目的人被解雇了，Twitter 约<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/04/12/tech/elon-musk-bbc-interview-twitter-intl-hnk/index.html">80%</a>的员工也被解雇了。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/02/elon-musk-twitter-ethics-algorithm-biases/673110/">阅读：我亲眼目睹埃隆·马斯克从内部扼杀了 Twitter 的文化</a><br><br>马斯克在支付业务方面确实有经验。他于 1999 年创立了一家在线银行（也称为 X.com），不久后与 Confinity 合并，成为 PayPal。如果不是马斯克在过去 15 个月里在众目睽睽之下在他最新的商业冒险中犯了错误，也许这会给他的超级应用想法带来一些可信度。他以其反动和阴谋性的政治观点疏远了广告商，使公司深陷债务，有时还通过限制用户可以看到的推文数量而<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-outage-elon-musk-user-restrictions/674609/">导致该平台无法使用</a>。根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/twitter-traffic-falls-under-elon-musk-threads-mastodon-bluesky-competition/">第三方</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/eastdakota/status/1678065025750294532?s=20">流量数据</a>，该平台在马斯克的领导下似乎正在萎缩。垃圾邮件<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/09/technology/elon-musk-twitter-spam-bots.html">猖獗</a>，最满意的用户似乎是以前被禁止的种族主义者和反犹太主义者，他们重新获得了扩音器的使用权。<br><br>对于马斯克来说，要让人们相信他的溅射平台是发布<em>巴本</em>海默模因的最佳场所已经很困难了，更不用说是……一切事物的正确归宿，包括我们的钱。但当你考虑解释 X 的第二种方式时，马斯克的声誉失血和他的宏伟野心之间的认知失调就更容易弥合了，即这是一次在黑暗中孤注一掷的尝试。<br><br> <strong>2. X 是<em>伪软件</em>——只是流行语和徽标。</strong><br><br>与 Facebook <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-metaverse-mark-zuckerberg/620538/">转向 Meta</a>的方向不同，Meta 是围绕一个真实的（尽管有缺陷且没有吸引力的）虚拟现实产品，X 是一个品牌重塑，只不过是一些模糊的流行语集合，拼凑在一起形成一个完整的句子。周日，亚卡里诺将即将推出的应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/lindayacc/status/1683213895463215104?s=20">描述</a>为“无限互动的未来状态”，“以音频、视频、消息、支付/银行业务为中心——为创意、商品、服务和机会创建一个全球市场。”她还指出，“在人工智能的支持下，X 将以我们刚刚开始想象的方式连接我们所有人。” （亚卡里诺没有回应置评请求。）<br><br>她的推文是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/galaxy-brain/630ec150bcbd490021b17eab/business-dudes-need-to-stop-talking-like-this/">商业人士<em>lorem ipsum</em></a>的近乎完美的例子——公司的胡言乱语，表面上听起来很聪明，但实际上却令人困惑。什么是“无限互动”？ X将如何“由AI驱动”？她指的是像 ChatGPT 这样的生成式人工智能，还是多年来为 Twitter 的“For you”提要提供支持的标准算法？细节无关紧要：这些词串在一起时听起来像<em>什么</em>就可以了。<br><br>马斯克也犯过这样的胡言乱语。他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/WatcherGuru/status/1683324036950966273?s=20">认为</a>，他的假设项目如果构建正确，可能“成为全球金融体系的一半”。这是业余爱好者的空洞语言，相当于我告诉你这篇文章如果写得正确，有望赢得普利策解释性新闻奖，或者我是<em>《大西洋月刊</em>》的《计算机话语》的执行文字匠部分。<br><br>马斯克和亚卡里诺对 X 的描述不仅仅意味着<em>“汽件”（vaporware）</em> ，这是一个行业术语，指的是一种从未实现的大肆宣传的产品。它们也感觉像是别的东西：我称之为<em>伪软件</em>。与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/galaxy-brain/6258e039dc551a00208cc5e1/elon-musk-meme-stocks-and-retail-investing-for-the-superrich/">伪事件</a>一样，伪软件伪装成具有新闻价值的事物，尽管事实并非如此。亚卡里诺的 Mad Libs-ian 推文风暴是这个伪事件的新闻稿：迄今为止已在装饰性变化中体现出来的支点的大讨论。马斯克的首要任务是采用新标志并将其<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RMac18/status/1683541303680987136?s=20">投影</a>在总部的会议室中。当 Yaccarino 发推文说“X 将以我们刚刚开始想象的方式将我们所有人联系起来”时，我相信她的话：似乎没有人花太多时间思考这一切。<br><br>人们很自然地想知道为什么世界上最富有的人会花时间拆除世界上最知名的社交媒体品牌之一，转而支持一个无人问津的神秘超级应用程序。他可以随时飞往私人岛屿，一边喝着无限量的冰镇果汁朗姆酒，一边咯咯地谈论狗狗币！这里有对X的第三个也是最重要的解释，那就是它是马斯克的声誉信用额度。<br><br> <strong>3.马斯克需要挽回面子。</strong><br><br>马斯克的声誉取决于人们相信他能够开辟新的工业类别，并能看到周围的角落，创造出未来的东西。他斥资 440 亿美元收购 Twitter 时提出了一个富有远见的框架：马斯克将实现 Twitter 成为真正的全球城镇广场的梦想，并大规模解决言论自由的棘手问题。在这方面失败后，马斯克本质上是在 X 回归基础——这是一个按照他自己的形象重塑互联网的机会。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-outage-elon-musk-user-restrictions/674609/">阅读：埃隆·马斯克这次真的打破了推特</a><br><br>正如<em>彭博社</em>的 Max Chafkin <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/chafkin/status/1683475959981264900/photo/2">指出的</a>那样，马斯克最初的 X.com 品牌彻底失败了。他对这个名字和网址很着迷，但消费者将这个品牌与成人娱乐网站联系起来，这并非不合逻辑。 2000 年合并后，马斯克被 X.com 董事会<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/was-elon-musk-fired-from-paypal/">驱逐</a>，一年后该服务更名为 PayPal，但这家支付公司仍然是他遗产的重要组成部分。那么，X 是对年轻版企业家的回想——他与成功、有效的产品和丰厚的投资者回报联系在一起。这也代表着未完成的事业以及重写他职业生涯早期阶段的机会。<br><br>从这个意义上说，X与其说是一个辉煌的愿景，不如说是一种绝望的行为。马斯克的行为很像一家烧钱速度不可持续的初创公司——他需要现金注入。为了筹集一些声誉资本，他需要一个好主意，一个看起来合理且可扩展的主意。 X 勾选了这个想法的所有方框。它的野心如此模糊以至于无边无际，这标志着永恒的增长和赚钱——毫不夸张地说，它是<em>一切</em>应用程序。这样，X对于任何仍然想相信马斯克的人来说都是一个墨迹测试：以正确的方式眯起眼睛，X就会呈现出该人对互联网未来的任何希望和梦想的形式。这就是伪软件的转瞬即逝的天才：营销一款应用程序的最大特点是，你几乎什么都不说就可以逃脱惩罚。<br><br>但到底有多少人仍然对马斯克抱有坚定的信心，这是一个悬而未决的问题。有多少人愿意对不能按时支付<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbctv18.com/technology/twitter-evicted-boulder-office-colorado-unpaid-rent-elon-musk-16949921.htm#:~:text=The%20company%20failed%20to%20pay,to%20non%2Dpayment%20of%20rent.">租金</a>和服务器<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.platformer.news/p/twitter-stiffs-google">费用</a>的人进行无罪推定？谁将帮助这位解雇了公司大部分股权​​并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/jul/12/twitter-severance-payments-lawsuit">据称</a>欠下 5 亿美元遣散费的人打造这家科技巨头？也许最重要的是，谁对马斯克将时间、精力和金钱集中在什么事情上感到兴奋？<br><br>尽管 X 想要做大，但与马斯克将自己推销为专家的项目相比，微信克隆在概念上还是很小的：太空探索、重新连接人类大脑、彻底改变交通以拯救地球。对X最愤世嫉俗的观点是，那些仍然尊重马斯克的人都是反动派，他们只有在敌人被兴高采烈地嘲笑时才感到高兴。那么，马斯克对社交网络的拆除也许是成功的，只要它让正确的人痛苦即可。由于别无选择，马斯克决定抵押 Twitter 品牌来拯救自己的品牌。即使按照他的标准，这也是一个冒险的赌注。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:56:12 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/</item></channel></rss>